\par }\pard \ql \fi-480\li480\ri0\sb120\sa120\widctlpar\tx515\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin480\itap0\pararsid6890657 {\f0\fs24\lang1033\langfe1033\langnp1033\insrsid6890657\charrsid11213751 I:\tab Could I have your full name please?
\par AH:\tab Annie Hogg B. Yes.
\par I:\tab Could I have your present address?
\par AH:\tab Darlington.
\par I:\tab And you're single?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Could you tell me the year you were born?
\par AH:\tab 1899. Yes.
\par I:\tab Where were you born?
\par AH:\tab Darlington.
\par I:\tab How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par AH:\tab Oh I'm afraid I can't tell you that.
\par I:\tab Did you move at all while you were still at school?
\par AH:\tab I didn't remember moving, we moved from there to Marshall Street.
\par I:\tab Which was the address where you were born?
\par AH:\tab Well I don't know the number but I know it was Havelock Street. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember roughly how long you lived there before you moved?
\par AH:\tab I would only be very small, I can't remember.
\par I:\tab Before you went to school would it be?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Oh yes.
\par I:\tab Where did you move to from there?
\par AH:\tab To Marshall Street.
\par I:\tab So would you say you were in Havelock Street just two or three years?
\par AH:\tab Yes, I should think so.
\par I:\tab Then you went to Marshall Street?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How many years did you live in Marshall Street, did you move at all before you left school?
\par AH:\tab Oh - yes. Yes I did. I should think perhaps six or seven years in Marshall Street. Yes.
\par I:\tab Where did you go then?
\par AH:\tab Then we went from there to Easson Road. We were getting a - a larger house all the time you see.
\par I:\tab How long were you in Easson Road?
\par AH:\tab Now - I think we were - only be there about three years and then we went to Salisbury Terrace. And we were fifteen years there. Yes.
\par I:\tab So that brings us to after the end of 1918?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab So in 1918 you'd be in Salisbury Terrace?
\par AH:\tab Yes, we would. Yes. Oh yes, we were in there long before the war - before 1914 when the war started.
\par I:\tab And you were still there at the end of the war?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You said the family moved to go to a larger house?
\par AH:\tab A - a larger house, every time, yes.
\par I:\tab All these moves were so you could go to a larger house?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par AH:\tab Twelve.
\par I:\tab How many boys and girls were there?
\par AH:\tab Six of each. Yes.
\par I:\tab And do you remember which order they came in, perhaps if you could start with the eldest?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Robert. Yes.
\par I:\tab Who came next?
\par AH:\tab George, Willie, and then it would be Tom I think. Then Margaret. And Janet. Oh - and Tom.
\par I:\tab You said three died as children?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes, three died as children. So -
\par I:\tab How old were they when they died, do you remember?
\par AH:\tab I can't remember the first two but I think the third would be about three-year-old and then Janet was eleven.
\par I:\tab All these were the children who were born before you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab So you never knew them?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Do you know how the three-year-old died?
\par AH:\tab The one that - well mother and father had been away and they came home and - of course in those days they had cabs and - as the - man that drove the cab was lifting the little girl out of the cab she hit her hea
d against the roof and she started having convulsions and she died from that.
\par I:\tab You don't know what the other two died of?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab So they called another one Tom after one they'd lost?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Who came after Tom?
\par AH:\tab Richard. And then Annie.
\par I:\tab That's you?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Then Percy. And Doris. And Lily. And Margaret.
\par I:\tab Margaret again was the same name?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab You were never lonely with a family that size were you?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Do you remember how many years, there were between them roughly? How many years older than you was Richard?
\par AH:\tab I think about - I think he was three-year-older than I was. Yes.
\par I:\tab And how many years older than you was Tom?
\par AH:\tab Eeh now - I - mother - mother seemed to have babies quickly.
\par I:\tab Was he very close to Richard do you think?
\par AH:\tab Oh no, Richard was older than - Tom was older than Richard. Well I - I should think there'd be two years in between.
\par I:\tab That'd make Tom about five years older than you?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Janet was one who died wasn't she?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How much older was - Margaret died didn't she?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Now Bob, the eldest one, how many years older than you was he?
\par AH:\tab Thirteen.
\par I:\tab So in between Bob and Tom, which is a space of eight years, there was George William who died, Margaret who died, and Janet who died? So your mother brought eight children up?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Have you got it right now?
\par AH:\tab Yes, she brought eight of us up.
\par I:\tab The eldest was thirteen years older than you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you know how much younger than you Percy was?
\par AH:\tab Eeh - three or four.
\par I:\tab Doris was younger than Percy?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How much younger than you was she?
\par AH:\tab Now Doris - I think I'm three-year-older than she is. Oh no. No. Wait a minute. How old is she. I think she's sixty-seven or sixty-eight.
\par I:\tab If Percy was three years younger Doris could be four, is that more like it?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab And how many years younger than you was Lily?
\par AH:\tab Now I think she was just a year younger than Doris. Yes.
\par I:\tab And Margaret?
\par AH:\tab Four years between - Lily and Margaret. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you know how old your father was when you were born?
\par AH:\tab I'm sorry I don't. I perhaps can give you those particulars later.
\par I:\tab You've no idea how old he was when he died?
\par AH:\tab Yes, I have that somewhere,
\par I:\tab But you can't tell me offhand?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Where did your father come from?
\par AH:\tab Felling. Felling Shore. Shore. Yes.
\par I:\tab Where's that?
\par AH:\tab Shove. Yes. That's - below - well, you know, there's Newcastle Gates at Felling.
\par I:\tab What did your father do?
\par AH:\tab He was a blacksmith.
\par I:\tab Did he serve his time as a blacksmith?
\par AH:\tab Yes. He did.
\par I:\tab Did he have any other job before he became a blacksmith?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did he have any other job after he became a blacksmith?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab He was a blacksmith all his life?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did he also do any casual or part time jobs?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab So he was a blacksmith all the way through until he died?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab How old was your mother when you were born?
\par AH:\tab I don't know - I know she was sixty-nine - when, she died.
\par I:\tab Do you know what year that was?
\par AH:\tab Oh dear. Well I can let you have that - later, yes.
\par I:\tab Did you know how much older or younger your father was than your mother?
\par AH:\tab Four years daddy was older. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Where did your mother come from?
\par AH:\tab Felling.
\par I:\tab Felling Shore again?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Had she any jobs before she married?
\par AH:\tab Yes - well she served her - served her time as a - bakeress. Yes.
\par I:\tab You were well looked after then as children were you?
\par AH:\tab Yes, we were.
\par I:\tab Did she have any other jobs before she married?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Just a bakeress?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did she work after she was married?
\par AH:\tab No. She was too busy.
\par I:\tab Did she do any part time jobs after she was married?
\par AH:\tab No, never.
\par I:\tab The house you lived in the longest, as a child would be Marshall Street wouldn't it?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab You lived there six or seven years?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How many rooms were there in the house at Marshall Street?
\par AH:\tab Three bedrooms. And a bathroom.
\par I:\tab How many rooms downstairs?
\par AH:\tab Sitting room and kitchen.
\par I:\tab Was it a sort of living kitchen or just a kitchen scullery?
\par AH:\tab That's it, kitchen - oh and a scullery. Yes, and a scullery.
\par I:\tab Could you describe the kitchen?
\par AH:\tab Well it was a - one that had the - had the set pot in for washing you know, a great big boiler and that.
\par I:\tab Did you use it as a living room or not?
\par AH:\tab No. No. That was where the cooking was done and that.
\par I:\tab You used the sitting room as a living room?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And you had three bedrooms?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sisters live in the house, did you have any relatives or lodgers living with you?
\par AH:\tab We had my grandma came.
\par I:\tab How old would you be when your grandmother came to live with you?
\par AH:\tab Well I should only - think I would only be about five year old.
\par I:\tab How long did your grandmother live with you?
\par AH:\tab Oh dear - she - until our Margaret was born and she was - the last one.
\par I:\tab So she lived with you quite a long time?
\par AH:\tab Yes, she did. Oh Margaret's - I can tell you Margaret's age. She's sixty-one.
\par I:\tab So that was 1905 - 1909?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab She was born in 1909?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab What happened to your grandmother then in 1909 when Margaret was born?
\par AH:\tab Well - it became a bit difficult, we wanted more room and that and - grandma went to live with her brother at Felling.
\par I:\tab So she left you in 1909?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your mother pay anyone to help in the house?
\par AH:\tab Yes. We had - we had a daygirl,
\par I:\tab No one living in?
\par AH:\tab No. No. Day girl,
\par I:\tab What were her duties?
\par AH:\tab Just helping mother. She would wash the floors and do the rough work.
\par I:\tab So she did the cleaning?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did she look after any of the children at all?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab What hours did she do, how many times a week?
\par AH:\tab Well it varied, if mother - if they got finished early mother let them go about three o'clock. She would start at nine in the morning.
\par I:\tab Until what time - about three o'clock?
\par AH:\tab Three o'clock, yes.
\par I:\tab You just had the one girl did you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did she come weekends as well?
\par AH:\tab No. Just - up to Friday. Yes, Monday to Friday.
\par I:\tab How did you get on with her?
\par AH:\tab Very well. Well during the years we had more than the one you know. Yes. But they were all very good. But when you come to think of it, it was just half a crown a day. Half a crown
 a week. Yes. Yes. But of course they got all their food and I know mother used to buy them aprons and - give them various things.
\par I:\tab What did you call the girls that came in?
\par AH:\tab Oh we had - Jenny.
\par I:\tab Did you call them by their Christian names?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes. Yes. Now - and Lily. Jenny and Lily. Oh I think we only had those two. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab And you just called them by their names?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab What did Jenny call you?
\par AH:\tab Annie. Yes.
\par I:\tab What did she call your mother?
\par AH:\tab Oh Mrs. B. Yes.
\par I:\tab And what did Lily call you?
\par AH:\tab The same. Yes.
\par I:\tab What did she call your mother?
\par AH:\tab Mrs. B.
\par I:\tab Was the washing done at home?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab It was done at home?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your mother or father mend or make the family's clothes?
\par AH:\tab My mother made our -
 our - all our underclothes. Yes. And mostly top ones as well. And we wore quite a lot of things in those days. You know - two petticoats and we all wore beautiful pinafores and white ones for Sundays and ordinary pinafores for through the week. Mother ha
d
 tremendous washing. Well when I got older I stayed at home and of course mother and I did the washing and sometimes it used to take us from nine 'till about four in the afternoon to do the washing. Well then you think, there were eight of us and father a
n
d mother every day and in those days - all the boys wore collared shirts to go to work. They wore long pants and thick vests. And collared shirts to go to work. And then - and dress shirts at night and then they wore - great long night shirts down to thei
r
 feet in flannelette. So you have an idea. And then there were three boys - Tom, Dick and Percy all worked as fitters and turners at the works and they had dirty greasy overalls. And father had moleskin trousers that we used to wash and they used to come 
white. And he wore navy blue flannel shirts and a red necktie. So he looked very nice when he used to go out to work.
\par I:\tab And he wore white trousers?
\par AH:\tab Yes. When they were washed they were just like - really white. And of course they used to have to be boiled and we had tremendous washings.
\par I:\tab Did Jenny or Lily ever help with the washing?
\par AH:\tab No. No, you see, there was grandma was there as well you see she helped as well.
\par I:\tab Your mother paid them just half a crown did she?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Your mother made your underclothes?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And some of your top clothes?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did she sew for the boys as well?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Made his - their shirts. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father make any of the clothes at all?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Were the clothes new or second hand?
\par AH:\tab No, we never had second hand clothes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember where they were bought? Any particular shop?
\par AH:\tab Well there was Jacques', they were at the bottom of Corporation Road. And then there was - Todd Brothers. And Frank Britton for hats. Yes. Britton. Yes.
\par I:\tab When did you have new clothes - any special time?
\par AH:\tab Well - you always got your new clothes for Easter. Mother always - made us new things for Easter.
\par I:\tab Any other time of the year did you have new clothes?
\par AH:\tab No, I don't think so. But my word, we 
had to take care of them when we came home in our - on a Sunday. We had to take our dresses off and put our others on and the pinafore. And - Sunday shoes were all cleaned on a Monday morning and put away in the cupboard and we never saw our Sunday clothe
s from one Sunday until the next Sunday.
\par I:\tab You even had different underclothes on?
\par AH:\tab I mean - shoes. Yes. And we never saw our - others until the next Sunday.
\par I:\tab Did your father mend your shoes at all?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab Where did you send those to be done?
\par AH:\tab There was a little shop in Salisbury Terrace called Mr. Addiman. He used to do them all.
\par I:\tab Did your mother mend your clothes as well?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes.
\par I:\tab Was she a good needlewoman?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Were your shoes always new or were they second hand sometimes?
\par AH:\tab No, not second-hand.
\par I:\tab Do you remember where your shoes were bought?
\par AH:\tab Mostly I think at Stanton's and the shop's still there now. Yes.
\par I:\tab When did you have new shoes, at Easter the same as your clothes?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Oh no, I think we had them more than Easter because you used to wear them out quickly.
\par I:\tab What other times would you have them? Just when you wore them out or any special time?
\par AH:\tab Yes. No, just when we wore them out.
\par I:\tab Did your father help your mother with any of the jobs in the house?
\par AH:\tab Well I've often heard mother say that when the babies were born, they ware born at home you know, there was no nursing homes in those days, and she's often said that father washed the floors and baked the bread and
 everything. When mother was - having the babies.
\par I:\tab So he could help with the cleaning then?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And he helped with the cooking?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did he help normal times?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab Not normally?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab She had to be out of action did she?
\par AH:\tab Well I mean there was - you see, there was grandma and - she had the girls. Normally he didn't help around the house.
\par I:\tab But he was able to do it when she needed it?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father help with the washing up at all?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did he light the fires?
\par AH:\tab No. Well you see, he went out to work early. They went out to work at six o' clock in the morning. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father do any decorating?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Who used to do that?
\par AH:\tab Well - mother had to get someone in to do it.
\par I:\tab Did he do any repairs or improvements to the house?
\par AH:\tab No, not as I know of.
\par I:\tab Do you remember if he ever helped with the children, did he ever dress or undress you?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes.
\par I:\tab He put you to bed sometimes did he?
\par AH:\tab Yes, and we always got a goodnight kiss. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember your father ever bathing you?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes. When we were little.
\par I:\tab Was that a regular thing or just an odd occasion?
\par AH:\tab Odd occasions.
\par I:\tab Did your father ever read to you?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did he ever tell you stories?
\par AH:\tab No. Mother did that.
\par I:\tab Did your father ever take you out without your mother?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab You never remember going out with hour father on your own?
\par AH:\tab No. Mother was always with us.
\par I:\tab Did your father ever look after you when your mother was out?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes.
\par I:\tab He would do that?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab When the need arose he was very useful?
\par AH:\tab Very useful, yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have any task that you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother and father?
\par AH:\tab Well of course when I became fourteen that was when I had to help in the house.
\par I:\tab When you left school?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab While you were still at school did you have any tasks you had to carry out regularly at home to help your mother and father?
\par AH:\tab Yes, darning. I used to darn the socks. And I used to - yes, and I used to do mending and -
\par I:\tab Did you do any other jobs?
\par AH:\tab And ironing. Yes.
\par I:\tab That was your special jobs was it?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you continue with these tasks after you left school?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, yes. I did - I did a lot more.
\par I:\tab After you left school what sort of tasks did you do?
\par AH:\tab Well I didn't - I - left school long before - before I was fourteen because I was - I wasn't - very well there, I was a bit of a weakling and I used to always
 have bronchitis every year. But I think that we were coddled too much, we - had too many clothes on. But after fourteen I never ailed anything at all.
\par I:\tab So you'd be thirteen when you left school would you?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Then what sort of jobs did you do in the home?
\par AH:\tab Well just carried on with the housework and things, helping mother.
\par I:\tab Did your mother still have the girls in when you left school or did she get rid of them?
\par AH:\tab Oh - she got rid of the maid, I was - I took over then.
\par I:\tab Did your brothers and sisters have any special jobs they had to do?
\par AH:\tab No. Boys got off very lightly in those days, we cleaned the shoes and did everything for them. The girl - did, yes.
\par I:\tab The other girls helped as well did they?
\par AH:\tab Oh no. I was the one that did the shoes and -
\par I:\tab You cleaned everybody's shoes?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Well of course, the girls - went out to work you see when they got older, at fourteen, and I was at home. Yes.
\par I:\tab Some of them would still be at school when you were at school wouldn't they?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they have any special jobs then, when they were still at school?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did the brothers and sisters younger than you have any special jobs that they had to do?
\par AH:\tab Well I think - Percy was an errand boy.
\par I:\tab But at home to help your mother and father?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, yes.
\par I:\tab Did they do any jobs at all?
\par AH:\tab Oh no.
\par I:\tab Did the older children help the younger with things they found difficult, such as dressing or eating?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab The older ones all helped the younger ones did they?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab I suppose they'd have to in a big family wouldn't they?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they help the younger ones in any other way you can remember?
\par AH:\tab They had to take them out when it was holidays we had to take the - Margaret out in the pushchair. Yes. Yes, we always had to have her. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did the younger children help the older children in any ways? You said you cleaned your older brothers shoes and what have you, did the one younger than you help?
\par AH:\tab Oh no. No. No.
\par I:\tab They had no special jobs?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What time did you have to go to bed?
\par AH:\tab Well mother used to pack the younger ones off about seven o'clock. And then we had to go about nine. And if mother was having visitors in we all went early. We had to - she used to be - children had to be seen and not heard in those days.
\par I:\tab So you went to bed and missed the fun did you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Your mother put you to bed; did anyone else put you to bed?
\par AH:\tab Well of course when I became older I had to help to put the other ones to bed. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did anyone else ever put you to bed?
\par AH:\tab Not that I can remember,
\par I:\tab Did your father put you to bed sometimes?
\par AH:\tab When we were younger, yes.
\par I:\tab Would that be any special occasion?
\par AH:\tab Oh I should think only if mother was ill.
\par I:\tab At what age did you put yourself to bed?
\par AH:\tab Oh goodness, I started at an early age.
\par I:\tab About how old would you be?
\par AH:\tab I should think about ten or eleven.
\par I:\tab And then you had to start putting the younger ones to bed as well?
\par AH:\tab Yes, Yes.
\par I:\tab There were eight children were there?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And your grandmother?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And your mother and father?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you share a bedroom with anyone?
\par AH:\tab Yes, we certainly did. The four girls were in the one bedroom.
\par I:\tab Did you actually share a bed with anyone or not?
\par AH:\tab Yes, we had to. Two in a bed. Yes.
\par I:\tab That was the four girls in one bedroom?
\par AH:\tab Yes. And four boys in the other bedroom. Father and mother.
\par I:\tab Where was your grandmother?
\par AH:\tab I don't - I think she must have been - I can't remember. Perhaps she would - I think she would be in the room we were, the girls.
\par I:\tab In with you?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes, because I can remember I had to sleep with her, when I was a little girl.
\par I:\tab Where would the others be - some hadn't been born had they?
\par AH:\tab No, no, that was it, yes.
\par I:\tab So you used to sleep with your grandmother while she was still there?
\par AH:\tab Yes. That's why I used to think in after years that - that was why I was ill. Because grandma would be draw
ing - you know - she would be living from me, old people do you know. Oh yes. I - that's what I - I think. Well old people should not sleep with young ones should they? No.
\par I:\tab You remember sleeping with her?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab After she left then you shared with one of your sisters?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What room did you bath in?
\par AH:\tab Oh we had a proper bathroom.
\par I:\tab In Marshall Street?
\par AH:\tab Yes. And - and Easson Road and Salisbury Terrace.
\par I:\tab How often did you have a bath?
\par AH:\tab Every Friday night. Yes.
\par I:\tab When did you have clean clothes to put on?
\par AH:\tab Every Friday.
\par I:\tab You changed all your underclothes?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Where did the family have the meals?
\par AH:\tab In the - kitchen. Yes. We had a great big table - enormous table.
\par I:\tab Were there any occasions when you had a meal in another room?
\par AH:\tab No. Always.
\par I:\tab Where did your mother cook?
\par AH:\tab In the back kitchen.
\par I:\tab The one that you had the meals in?
\par AH:\tab No, in the back scullery. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of cooking equipment did she use?
\par AH:\tab A gas oven.
\par I:\tab Did you have any sort of range in the kitchen?
\par AH:\tab Yes, we had a big - an old range with an oven. And she used that, yes.
\par I:\tab And also a gas oven in the scullery?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab When was breakfast eaten, what time?
\par AH:\tab We had to go to school at nine o'clock so it would be about eight o'clock.
\par I:\tab Which members of the family would be present, you told me your father went out early?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab So what did he do for breakfast?
\par AH:\tab And the boys - the boys all went out early to work you see and - they used to have their breakfast before they went. Mother used to have to get up early you know. Yes. Yes. Yes. And then of course we had ours before we went to school.
\par I:\tab When did your mother have her breakfast?
\par AH:\tab Oh she had it with us. Yes.
\par I:\tab So the men folk had it together?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab The ones who were going to work?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And then the younger ones had it with your mother?
\par AH:\tab Yes, afterwards. But we all were together on a Saturday and a Sunday.
\par I:\tab For breakfast?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. Father used to say those that didn't come down for nine o'clock on a Sunday morning, they didn't get any breakfast.
\par I:\tab So you couldn't have any lie in?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab What did you usually eat and drink for breakfast?
\par AH:\tab Well it was just - a bit of bacon or an egg or bread and butter and - a jam. Something like that you know.
\par I:\tab Did your father and brothers have a cooked breakfast or not?
\par AH:\tab Not always. Not always.
\par I:\tab So it was the same sort of thing?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab It was usually a bit of bacon?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes, mother used to buy a big piece of the stores on a Friday and she used to cut it up herself.
\par I:\tab And fry it as need be?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab On Sundays did you have anything different for breakfast when you all sat together?
\par AH:\tab Well it was always bacon and egg and sausage on a Sunday morning. Yes.
\par I:\tab What was Saturday's breakfast?
\par AH:\tab Oh, just the ordinary. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab When did you have your main meal, your dinner, did you have that in the middle of the day or at night?
\par AH:\tab 
Oh middle of the day. But of course father's had to be sent to work. A young boy used to come and mother used to wrap it up in a - a basket. And he used to have it at work every day, she had to cook a dinner and a boy used to come for it and - yes, send a
 hot meal every day for him. Yes.
\par I:\tab How many of you were usually present for your dinner? Did the other boys who were working come in for dinner?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, they came home, yes, yes. All but father. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What did you usually have to eat and drink - what did you drink for breakfast time?
\par AH:\tab Tea.
\par I:\tab All of you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember anything specially you had to eat or drink at dinnertime?
\par AH:\tab Oh - my word, my mother - well I was just saying, we used to have a - an earthenware bowl, brown outs
ide and cream in, and my mother used to buy two rabbits and three pound of shin beef and two black puddings and she used to make a pie. Yes, that went in - for dinnertime. And then of course she used to do - boiled puddings, boiled fruit puddings and - st
e
ak and kidney puddings. I - my mother said she didn't think there was a part of a bullock that she hadn't cooked. She was - she looked after us and we had good food, practically all her money went on good food for us. And big pans of soup with - two and a
 
half pounds of thin boiling meat in and then vegetables and - and sometimes she used to get a nice piece of bacon and boil that and - make soup after. We had wonderful meals and I never remember having anything but a leg of pork or a - big piece or sirloi
n or a leg of lamb on a Sunday, for our Sunday dinner. And Yorkshire puddings and - she was a marvellous cook. Yes. She was wonderful.
\par I:\tab Has she passed it on to you, are you a good cook?
\par AH:\tab Well, not bad and of course she could bake beautiful cakes and we've all done that. Mother's baking day twice a week used to be a stone of white flour, half stone of brown and a dozen teacakes. That was - that was without any pastry or anything.

\par I:\tab They worked hard in those days didn't they?
\par AH:\tab Very hard - my mother was never done really.
\par I:\tab She wouldn't with a large family to look after would she?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you have anything to drink at dinnertime?
\par AH:\tab No. Just water.
\par I:\tab And Sundays you usually had a joint?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You had your dinner at dinnertime, what sort of tea arrangements did you have?
\par AH:\tab Well - all the younger ones had their tea before the older ones came from work you see. We used to have it at soon as we got in from school.
\par I:\tab What sort of a tea was that?
\par AH:\tab Well - you know bread and butter and cake. Yes, and just afternoon tea, we never had any meat or anything at tea.
\par I:\tab Did you have anything else before you went to bed?
\par AH:\tab Just a drink and a piece of bread and butter.
\par I:\tab What sort of a drink would you have at bedtime?
\par AH:\tab Well I don't remember - it was mostly water I think. Well none of these fancy things had come in in those days had they? No.
\par I:\tab When the men folk came in what sort of a tea did they have?
\par AH:\tab Oh there was always a meat tea for father and - the boys, they got something.
\par I:\tab They had a high tea?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they drink anything with their tea?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did the grown ups have anything when they went to bed?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes. Yes. Well on a Saturday night that was a special night, mother used to get a piece of fish about this big. She used to do it in the oven and do mashed potatoes and that and that was supper on Saturday night.
\par I:\tab Just for the grown ups or did you all have it?
\par AH:\tab No, we all - yes. Yes. Just on Saturday.
\par I:\tab Was Sunday supper any different?
\par AH:\tab Well we just had sandwiches that were left over from the joint on a Sunday night.
\par I:\tab But during the week you didn't bother?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Your grandmother was still with you then wasn't she, when did she have her meals?
\par AH:\tab With all of us. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab So she'd join in all these meals?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your mother or father bake their own bread?
\par AH:\tab Mother did. And father could bake it when mother was ill. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your mother make her own jam?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father ever make jam?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Do you remember any particular type of jam your mother made?
\par AH:\tab Mostly plum jam I think, we used to love plum jam. Yes. We did. And damson, she used to do, and strawberry.
\par I:\tab Did she bottle any fruit or vegetables?
\par AH:\tab No, it wasn't done in those days. No.
\par I:\tab Did your mother make pickles at all?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did she ever make any brine?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did your father ever make any wine?
\par AH:\tab Oh no, now wait a bit, she used to get the bottle of essence at Christmas and make ginger wine. That was the only wine.
\par I:\tab How did you do that?
\par AH:\tab Well you just - added boiling water and sugar to this - that you bought. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father or mother make any medicines for the family?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Any cough mixtures or anything like that?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Was any beer brewed for the family?
\par AH:\tab Never.
\par I:\tab Did your father or mother grow their own vegetables and fruit?
\par AH:\tab Father did, yes, he had an allotment. While we were in Marshall Street. Just at the bottom. You see, when we lived there it was all green fields, there was no houses and that there.
\par I:\tab What did he grow?
\par AH:\tab Well - potatoes and turnips and cabbage and - things like that.
\par I:\tab It's useful to have when you've got a large family isn't it?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember if they bought any vegetables and fruit?
\par AH:\tab Well sometimes if - when they were finished in the garden we had to. And of course mother bought oranges and things for us, we all - got all those when we were little. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father grow any fruit?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you ever have any tinned vegetables or tinned fruit?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Or any dried vegetables or dried fruit?
\par AH:\tab No. I don't think it was heard of in those days. No. No.
\par I:\tab It was fresh stuff or nothing wasn't it?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they keep any livestock far the family, any hens, pigs or goats?
\par AH:\tab Well when he had the allotment he had we had hens. We got the eggs, yes.
\par I:\tab That would be a help wouldn't it?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Who looked after the hens?
\par AH:\tab Father.
\par I:\tab How many times a week did you eat meat?
\par AH:\tab Well practically every day. Yes. 'Cos mother did oxtail and all kinds of things. And we used - well when we were at school some of the children used to laugh at us having liver and bacon and that for dinner you k
now. But when you come to think of it now it was one of the best things you could possibly have wasn't it.
\par I:\tab You had a really good balanced diet didn't you?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, we did.
\par I:\tab Did you ever have any tinned meat?
\par AH:\tab No. Never.
\par I:\tab Did you ever get any of the rabbits from poaching?
\par AH:\tab No. They used to be about nine pence each when I was a girl, rabbit.
\par I:\tab And you put two rabbit in a pie?
\par AH:\tab Yes. I used to love rabbit pie when I was little.
\par I:\tab Do you remember seeing your mother having less food so that the family could have more?
\par AH:\tab No, never.
\par I:\tab You all had fair shares did you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father ever have more to eat than the rest of you?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Were you allowed to talk during meals or not?
\par AH:\tab Well father didn't like it, we never had to - there was never a wrong word at our dinner table or anything, we all -
\par I:\tab Could you talk at all?
\par AH:\tab Oh we could talk, yes. No squabbles, no.
\par I:\tab Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par AH:\tab T
here was only once, I couldn't - oh I couldn't stand vegetable soup. My mother used to make it thick you know with vegetables and things and I used to keep at the dinner table 'til it was nearly school time because I wouldn't eat this vegetable soup. Thin
k however in the end she used to give me something else to go to school with. Yes. But you know if she'd only thought to strain it I'd have been all right, but oh - terribly thick - and I just couldn't stand it.
\par I:\tab What was your parent's attitude if you left some food uneaten on the plate?
\par AH:\tab Well we didn't ever.
\par I:\tab But what about this vegetable soup?
\par AH:\tab Oh I didn't like that.
\par I:\tab It'd be taken away in the end?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab But they had a good try to make you eat it?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt could you ask someone to pass it to you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Or did you have to wait until it was offered to you?
\par AH:\tab Oh no, we could ask.
\par I:\tab Could you ask for a second helping?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you get it?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Were you told how to hold them?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How were you told to hold your knife and fork?
\par AH:\tab How do you mean?
\par I:\tab Did you get any instructions on how to hold your knife and fork?
\par AH:\tab Oh father taught us how to hold our knife and fork.
\par I:\tab Just the normal way?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Were you told to sit in a certain way or not?
\par AH:\tab Yes. You're not to lounge, we had to sit up straight.
\par I:\tab Could you bring toys or a book to the table?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab When could you leave the table?
\par AH:\tab When we asked mother or father if we could leave.
\par I:\tab You could get down as soon as you'd finished could you?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. If we wanted.
\par I:\tab When you could all the family sat at the table for the meal?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did the younger ones join you; do you remember where the younger ones had their meals?
\par AH:\tab Well they - had a little chair.
\par I:\tab She came to the table with you then as soon as she could?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you always have the same places at table?
\par AH:\tab Oh no. Father and mother had their places but -
\par I:\tab Where did they sit?
\par AH:\tab Head of the table.
\par I:\tab And the others?
\par AH:\tab Where you could, yes.
\par I:\tab Who served the meal?
\par AH:\tab Mother.
\par I:\tab What order were you served in, did she serve anybody first when you were all together?
\par AH:\tab Well I think the eldest got it first.
\par I:\tab Were you served in any special order or not?
\par AH:\tab I can't remember - I don't think so.
\par I:\tab The younger brothers and sisters sat in little chairs near the table before they could feed themselves?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Who fed them?
\par AH:\tab Mother.
\par I:\tab When you had the help where did they have their meals?
\par AH:\tab Oh they always sat at the table with us. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they have any different food?
\par AH:\tab No, just the same.
\par I:\tab Was your mother an easy person to talk to?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, she was lovely. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did she show you lots of affection?
\par AH:\tab Yes, she did but she knew how to keep us in our place, and it was mother who did the chastising, not
 father. Not - father never touched one of us. It was always mother did. Mother used to think a man had a too hard a hand to chastise children. So she did that, she had a belt. Yes.
\par I:\tab And she used it?
\par AH:\tab She did.
\par I:\tab You say she read to you at night and things like that?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did she show you affection at all?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes. But she could be very strict - we had to do as we were told. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab If you had any worries could you share them with her?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. We told mother. Yes.
\par I:\tab How about your father, was he an easy person to talk to?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, and he loved every one of us. He used to say - when the last baby was born, he always used to say he wished mother could have twins. He loved children, he loved children.
\par I:\tab Did he show you affection as well?
\par AH:\tab Yes, very much. We've always thought all of us that he was one of the best fathers that anybody could ever have.
\par I:\tab Could you share your worries with your father as well?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You were lucky being able to talk to both of them weren't you?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You must have had a happy home life?
\par AH:\tab We were a very happy home.
\par I:\tab How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par AH:\tab Well we had to respect - you know. We weren't allowed to just - just do anything and - and if - of course if we did, well, we got corrected.
\par I:\tab Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in certain, ways?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How did you have to behave towards each other?
\par AH:\tab We
ll there was - never any quarrelling in front of father and mother else we would have known about it. No, we've been a family that's thought a lot about each other, all - every bit of the time - right through life we've kept together. We never had any rea
l bad squabbles at all. You had your little childish - yes.
\par I:\tab Did they say you should hit back or not if another child hurt you?
\par AH:\tab No. Mother didn't believe in that. No. No.
\par I:\tab No violence?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par AH:\tab Well we were always sent to Sunday school. Every Sunday morning at nine o'clock and then we went into church after Sunday school. And then in the afternoon we went to Sunday school at two o'clock again. And at night we went to chapel at six.

\par I:\tab So you had a full day on Sunday?
\par AH:\tab Yes, we had. Father and - you never were allowed to sew or do anything on a Sunday - or play with toys, you could read a book. Not do anything else on a Sunday. Mother never washed or - nothing was - li
ke that was done on a Sunday. It was Sunday - special day.
\par I:\tab What kind of people then do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par AH:\tab To be good. Yes.
\par I:\tab What do you consider a good person?
\par AH:\tab Well - I just don't know, I mean - try to lead a good life and be kind.
\par I:\tab Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?
\par AH:\tab Telling the truth. We must tell the truth. Yes. We had to.
\par I:\tab Any other things they taught you were particularly important in life?
\par AH:\tab I just can't think at present but I - I know mother's standards were -
\par I:\tab Were there any particular things your parents thought were wrong and taught you that they were wrong to do?
\par AH:\tab Oh - fighting and that. We wouldn't - hear of that at all. No, they wouldn't. We had - we had such a happy home. You had your little bits of - you know, fall outs with each other over little things but it was soon over and forgotten.
\par I:\tab What did your parents think of swearing?
\par AH:\tab My word, it would have been awful. Yes, it would.
\par I:\tab So you weren't allowed to swear?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par AH:\tab No. We weren't - it was sort of children had to be seen and not heard in those days.
\par I:\tab You had to wait until you were spoken to did you?
\par AH:\tab Yes, yes.
\par I:\tab If you did something your parents disapproved of what would happen, you've told me some of it haven't you?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. Mother did that, yes.
\par I:\tab What did she do?
\par AH:\tab She used the belt. Yes.
\par I:\tab Where?
\par AH:\tab Usually on our - yes, on your bottom, never on our legs or hands, you know, or - hitting you across the - the ears or anything like that, never that way, it was always your bottom that got it.
\par I:\tab Did she treat you all alike?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Everybody, yes.
\par I:\tab How often did you need to be punished?
\par AH:\tab Oh not often. No. No.
\par I:\tab Any particular one of you that got punished more than the others?
\par AH:\tab No, I don't think so.
\par I:\tab So it wasn't very often?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did your father ever chastise you at all?
\par AH:\tab Never.
\par I:\tab Do you remember any particular occasion when you were punished?
\par AH:\tab Eeh no. I don't. Just if I was naughty I would get - a slap. No
\par I:\tab How did you feel about being punished? Did you mind?
\par AH:\tab No. No. I - I'm one of, those think - that think if you're naugh
ty you should be punished. They don't believe in it today. Never get touched do they. It never did us any harm. And mother - when we used to go home from school and say we'd had the cane mother would - used to say, well it serves you right, you've done so
mething else you wouldn't have had the cane. She wouldn't have you - she wouldn't go back to school like the mothers do nowadays if their children get punished. Yes, yes.
\par I:\tab So you accepted your punishment?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents, or did one play a more important part than the other?
\par AH:\tab No, I think they were both the same. Of course it was mother that sent us to Sunday school and all that but father saw we went as well you know.
\par I:\tab So it was a joint effort?
\par AH:\tab Yes. It was a joint effort.
\par I:\tab When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, we always had a birthday cake. It wasn't always one of these fancy ones, sometimes mother used to make a one - 
you know - sort of pastry. We used to call them flat cakes. And she used to roll it out - it had currants and spice in - and she used to do it on the bottom shelf in the oven, and butter it hot. It was beautiful. That was our birthday cake,
\par I:\tab Did you receive presents on your birthday?
\par AH:\tab Yes, always, we always got something nice on our birthday.
\par I:\tab Did your brothers and sisters give you presents as well?
\par AH:\tab No, just our parents. Until we got older, then we started giving each other the presents.
\par I:\tab Did you have anything else that was special to eat on your birthday?
\par AH:\tab Well it was a proper - nice tea. Yes, yes, special tea.
\par I:\tab Did you have any guests, did you have any other people in?
\par AH:\tab Not until we got older. No, we didn't - we never had a children's party like that. No.
\par I:\tab Can you remember anything you did with your mother or father together on Christmas Day?
\par AH:\tab On Christmas Day was the loveliest day of all. Well - father - of course we used to be awake about six o'clock on Christmas morning, and father used to carry the youngest one downstairs and we all tripped after him. And -
\par I:\tab In order?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab In order of age?
\par AH:\tab Yes, yes. And of course we had a - a fireplace and we had a brass rod from end to end and we all hung our stockings on there and
 we had a - a big steel fender with a - when we used to come downstairs there was all kinds of things along the fender and all the - absolutely chock-a-block with toys. And father and mother used to go out on Christmas Eve and buy all the toys and that at
 Buckle's, it was a marvellous toyshop. And - and father never went out on a Christmas Day, he stayed in with all of us and it was a - a real happy day, we always had a goose and - all nice things you know. It was a wonderful day.
\par I:\tab Did you go to church on Christmas Day?
\par AH:\tab No. No, we stayed in.
\par I:\tab Did you play games on Christmas Day?
\par AH:\tab Party games, yes.
\par I:\tab Just your parents and you?
\par AH:\tab All of you, yes, yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of games did you play?
\par AH:\tab Well - we used to do charades and
 - yes, yes, we used to do that and guessing games and muffin man - here comes the muffin man and all those things when you were children. It was a lovely day and of course we were allowed to stay up later on Christmas Day. And always had a - a lovely tea
 and a lovely supper, it was a real -
\par I:\tab What time did you go to bed then on Christmas Day?
\par AH:\tab Oh it would be about ten o'clock. A really lovely - lovely day.
\par I:\tab Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par AH:\tab We had a piano.
\par I:\tab Who played the piano?
\par AH:\tab Well of course that was when we were all getting older, my sister, she went.
\par I:\tab Would that be before the end of 1918?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab Did you have any musical instruments before then at all?
\par AH:\tab Me father had a concertina.
\par I:\tab He played that did he?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did anybody else play it?
\par AH:\tab No, just father, and he could - he had a mouth organ as well. And he used to have a - wooden betty he'd carved himself. A wooden betty, like a wooden doll - with joints, all it's - it had all joints - it's arms and le
gs. And he used to put a plank in between his knees and he used to sing and play this mouth organ with one hand and knock on here and the doll used to dance for us when we were children.
\par I:\tab Like a puppet?
\par AH:\tab Yes, a puppet. And he made it, yes. And he -
\par I:\tab And he entertained the family did he?
\par AH:\tab Yes, he did.
\par I:\tab Haw often did he play to you?
\par AH:\tab Oh quite often. We used to love it. Oh yes. And of course daddy was a beautiful singer. Well all our boys - they were all tenors and all had lovely voices and 
of course when we all got together we used to have singsongs and - we always used to sing carols on Christmas Day. Yes.
\par I:\tab Can you sing too?
\par AH:\tab Yes, I was in the choir for - oh - about - thirty-five years.
\par I:\tab Could you all sing then, could your mother sing as we11?
\par AH:\tab Mother was a lovely singer, yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you ever make music together as a family?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab So your father played and you all sang?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Could you describe a musical evening that you had?
\par AH:\tab Well we just used to - well before we had the piano we used to sing and - father used to sing all sort of the old things, 'Genevieve' and - all those - 'Home Sweet Home', all those old songs.
\par I:\tab Did he play the concertina for that as well?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Or did you sing unaccompanied?
\par AH:\tab Oh we sang a lot of it unaccompanied. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have any special day when you sort of made music together as a family?
\par AH:\tab Well mostly on Sunday night we used to sings hymns. Of course that was a bit further on, when we had a piano.
\par I:\tab But before you had the piano did you have any special days?
\par AH:\tab Well it was mostly Sunday. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your parents play games with you other than at Christmas time?
\par AH:\tab No. Well - of course that would be later - we used to play dominoes and that.
\par I:\tab When would that be?
\par AH:\tab I suppose they - he would play with us on Christmas Day when we were children because we got games you know.
\par I:\tab So you think your mother and father joined in with - playing with you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they play any outdoor games with you at all?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Were there any books in the house?
\par AH:\tab Yes, plenty.
\par I:\tab What sort of books?
\par AH:\tab Children's books. And of course when we went to Sunday school we used to get prizes for - I used to get a prize nearly every year, 'Little Women' and all these lovely books.
\par I:\tab Was this for attendance?
\par AH:\tab Yes, for attendance at the school. We always got prizes. I've passed a few of mine on to my nephews and nieces. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were there any newspapers in the house?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you know what newspaper you got?
\par AH:\tab Well it would be the 'Echo' wouldn't it. And then mother always used to have 'Sunday Companion'.
\par I:\tab Was that a special newspaper?
\par AH:\tab Yes, that was a special Sunday paper. That was all.
\par I:\tab Did you have any magazines in the house?
\par AH:\tab No. The only ones I can remember were quite a - a bundle we had in the bottom of our press and it was - they were all about the Boer War.
\par I:\tab Do you remember your mother or father reading?
\par AH:\tab Mother used to read but father couldn't read. Father had never been taught to read.
\par I:\tab Couldn't he read at all?
\par AH:\tab No. But mother - he - he could sign his name, mother got him - he did some writing, taught him writing and that but - you see - they didn't go to school like we do now. But - and mother's mother had to pay for her, tuppence a wee
k to go to school - in those days. But father never had it - but do you know, he was wonderful. He could - the way he could get his jobs and everything, he used to get the men to tell him the - the sketches that he had to do his job and he could do it per
fectly.
\par I:\tab Even though he couldn't read the plans for himself?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. He was a real clever man. But he was never taught to read or write.
\par I:\tab Did your mother ever read aloud to your father as well as to you?
\par AH:\tab I never heard her.
\par I:\tab Do you remember a funeral in the family?
\par AH:\tab Well, only my father and mother.
\par I:\tab That would be after 1918?
\par AH:\tab And I - I do know we had a dreadful time when my brother Dick was killed in France.
\par I:\tab During the war?
\par AH:\tab Yes. During the war.
\par I:\tab What do you remember about that?
\par AH:\tab Well we just - he was killed before he was twenty-one. And - we just got a telegram to say that - first of all he was wounded. He was wounded at the Battle of Luz. And he had shrapnel wounds in his legs. And as soon as 
he got better they sent him back and I don't think he was in France two days that he was killed. So - that was an awful blow to mother, mother was - mother went - she lost weight she - we thought we were going to lose her. On account of Dick but eventuall
y
 father had to be stern and that with her you know and - he had - he brought her back because she was just letting herself go, she was - well to keep the boy 'til he's twenty-one and then lose him, it's terrible. He was a lovely boy. He never wanted to go
 to war in the first place. I think that was the hardest thing that ever happened to mother. And all of us, we were all terribly upset.
\par I:\tab Do you remember a funeral at all in the family before the end of 1918?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Were you taken out visiting neighbours, friends or relations?
\par AH:\tab We were taken to my Uncle Robert's.
\par I:\tab Where did he live?
\par AH:\tab In Woodlands Road.
\par I:\tab How often did you go there?
\par AH:\tab He was a councillor. Well, not very often. Special - there were special occasions when we went there. But - we
 had no other relations in the town you see. Just the one lot. See all of them lived at Newcastle, sometimes we all used to get taken to the Felling and I used to go - and there were four - my three brothers and I, we used to go a month to my grandma's in
 the summer. Yes. And stay with her. It was lovely.
\par I:\tab Did you visit friends at all, were you ever taken out visiting friends?
\par AH:\tab Well you see there was such a lot of us. Sometimes I went with mother to visit one, of her friends.
\par I:\tab Where would that be?
\par AH:\tab That was in Darlington.
\par I:\tab But you occasionally went with your mother to visit friends?
\par AH:\tab Yes. You see, I was the eldest girl. And I was sort of mother's right hand you know.
\par I:\tab Did you ever visit neighbours at all?
\par AH:\tab Well - no, we had - two - we had two good neighbours. They were very good. And the next door neighbour, she had about eight children and - we were very friendly with both neighbours. But never went in and out each other's houses.
\par I:\tab Were you friendly with the neighbours in Marshall Street?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you visit them at all?
\par AH:\tab Well I can't remember.
\par I:\tab You said you didn't go out with your father on his own?
\par AH:\tab I do.
\par I:\tab But did you ever go out with your mother and father?
\par AH:\tab Yes. I went out with mother and father, they used to take four of us out on a Sunday night. Walk us to the South Park or right away round Cockerton where it was all green fields. And then grandma would look after the younger ones you see while -

\par I:\tab So that would be your three brothers and you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Were you taken shopping at all?
\par AH:\tab On a Monday I used to go out with mother. Every Monday to the market. Oh yes, yes, every Monday.
\par I:\tab What do you remember about the Monday market?
\par AH:\tab Oh it was a special
 day and - in those days - I really used to be terrified of when we were going because - they used to bring all the cattle from Larchfield Street, it was the cattle market in Larchfield Street. Yes. They used to bring - where the new school is - they used
 
to bring the cattle right away - through - down Salisbury Terrace to the North Road Station to ship them. And all used to pass our door. Salisbury Terrace. And sometimes they got sway and down the back lane - I used to be terrified. Yes, yes, but we alway
s went to town on Monday afternoon and - it was a special day.
\par I:\tab Did you do the weeks shopping then?
\par AH:\tab Oh no. Mother had - the stores was just at the top of our road and we had the stores and we had a Post Office and we had the cobblers and we had the gr
ocers on the corner, we had a fruit shop and cake shop - Ward's cake shop. So I mean we didn't have to go far to do our shopping you see. Mother used to have a big order at the weekend.
\par I:\tab So what did you go into the market for?
\par AH:\tab Just to look round for scraps for mother to make things. Yes, yes. Mother used to get all the materials down in the market. And her curtaining and - she used to make all her own curtains.
\par I:\tab She sounds very clever?
\par AH:\tab Yes, she was a wonderful mum. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You don't remember ever going out with just your father?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Do you remember any other outings with your parents?
\par AH:\tab Well they used to - every year he used to take us away for a days outing - to the seaside, always to Redcar or Saltburn.
\par I:\tab When would that be?
\par AH:\tab 
It was on Saturday. Because he had Saturday off you see. Saturday afternoon off or - or sometimes, when he had holidays, he always took us away for day I can remember when we were going - from - by - from North Road Station once. He knew the man who was t
aking the tickets as we went through you know to get on the platform. And when he saw father he just said, pass battalion. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you all go then?
\par AH:\tab Yes, oh yes, we all went.
\par I:\tab Did your grandma used to go too?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes, we had a lovely outing, m
other used to make ham and egg pies and all kinds. Yes. And at Easter he used to take us to Gainford and we used to go down by the river. And used - she used to pack a basket then and we all used to have our - now sometimes when we went there our friends 
went with us. You see, the boys had pals there, well they used to be invited too and we used to have a really big time.
\par I:\tab Do you remember doing anything special on Bank Holidays with your parents?
\par AH:\tab 
No. We were - everyone of us - we were very keen on walking. On a Sunday after I came out of Sunday school on a Sunday afternoon I used to walk to South Park and back, have me tea, go to chapel and then after chapel - walk to the South Park and right away
 
round Carmel Road back to Salisbury Terrace. Well - we did an awful lot of walking. I don't think the young people nowadays do enough walking. Yes. Go to school in the car, they're not - know how to use their legs like we used to. And then of course - the
n
 it was - Whitsuntide and times like that, the church - they always had a ramble. And we used to go to Richmond and then walk right over Willance's Leap and all these places. Through Billy Banks Woods and - oh it was lovely. All take our picnic you know. 
Our food for a picnic.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go away for a holiday, you said you went to your grandmothers?
\par AH:\tab Yes, to my grandma's. Yes.
\par I:\tab And you stayed far a month?
\par AH:\tab Month.
\par I:\tab Where was that?
\par AH:\tab Felling Shore.
\par I:\tab Did you go regularly every year?
\par AH:\tab Well - every year until grandma died. She had twelve children too.
\par I:\tab You'd have a lovely time with your cousins then?
\par AH:\tab Lovely. We were just let run wild.
\par I:\tab Which members of the family when, your three older bothers and you?
\par AH:\tab And me.
\par I:\tab What did you do?
\par AH:\tab 
Oh we had a lovely time because - grandma had a - lovely cottage she lived in, this lovely big cottage with a great big garden. And then of course the boys got on with the boys of the village and they used to go off with them and I had - aunties, plen
ty of aunties at Newcastle and they used - and my Uncle Billy used to take me to Jesmond Dene and Heaton and Wallsend, all over. Yes. And - not only that, my Aunt Mary Jane had a - inn at the Felling Shore and the ships used to come in to the quay and of 
c
ourse they all used to come in to the pub. And - as a little girl my cousin Lizzie lived there and she - I used to be often there. And sometimes I used to slip through to - to her and I used to meet some of the sailors. And I can remember once they took C
ousin Lizzie on - and I - on to a - Brazilian battleship And they took me right to the top of the mast.
\par I:\tab How old would you be then?
\par AH:\tab I would be about twelve. And then - eeh I can always remember that - they gave me a big cedar stick, one of those hard 
things they used to eat at sea in those days and then they passed one of these enormous boxes of chocolates, I'd never seen such a box of chocolates come round. And of course they were all black you know, the men. And me being a little white girl and all 
dressed in the white dress and everything - oh - they were wonderful to me. They even showed me the flags that had been in - battle. And also in glass because if you'd blown on them or anything they would have gone to pieces. I had some lovely times.

\par I:\tab Could you tell me how you spent Saturdays in those days?
\par AH:\tab Saturdays - well I used to - yes, still at school - oh we just used to go in the park and play. We had a lovely park - North Lodge Park was there you know. And that was when they had the old boathou
se and the boats on the lake when I was a girl. Yes, there was a lovely old boathouse. They used to say it was haunted. But they eventually pulled it down but - there was a lovely pond there with - boats and that. Yes, we used - lovely time in the park. W
ell you see we weren't very far from the park. We used to go every night after school. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Sundays you went to Sunday school and church and Sunday school and church?
\par AH:\tab Sunday school and church. And then for a walk afterwards. And had to be in at nine o'clock. I've seen me - I've been with some girls and boys, we've got to Linden Avenue and I knew once I ran all the way home to he home for nine o'clock. Yes.

\par I:\tab You said you had different clothes on Sunday?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And you play any games on Sunday?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did your parents think it wrong to work or play on Sunday?
\par AH:\tab Well we didn't - they thought Sunday was Sunday, it had to be kept as such.
\par I:\tab You were just allowed to read did you say?
\par AH:\tab Yes. We could read our books.
\par I:\tab How about sewing or knitting?
\par AH:\tab No. Nothing. No. And we used to get a nice orange on a Sunday. Sunday afternoon after we came from Sunday school. Of course they were very cheap those days, oranges.
\par I:\tab Did your parents attend a place of worship or not?
\par AH:\tab Mother did. But father just went when it was anniversary or special occasion. Well I expect he looked after the family while my mother went, yes.
\par I:\tab Which church was it?
\par AH:\tab Corporation Road Methodist. Which is now pulled down.
\par I:\tab Is that the one that you went to?
\par AH:\tab Yes, I went there from being in the primary department. Until - is if five years ago. Yes, yes, all the time.
\par I:\tab How often did your mother go to church?
\par AH:\tab Every Sunday night. Yes. And in latter years daddy used to go with her every Sunday night.
\par I:\tab But not when you were young?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab How many of the children went with her, you went and how many others?
\par AH:\tab There was - just the boys and I, three boys and -
\par I:\tab The older ones?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Well grandma used to go sometimes because - sometimes 
mother didn't go and grandma used to go if mother wasn't well and I know she had an umbrella with a handle on and I know if us - the boys or I spoke in chapel we used to get this on the feet. Yes. Oh we weren't supposed to talk or anything when you were i
n church. Aren't things very different today.
\par I:\tab You had your Sunday clothes?
\par AH:\tab Sunday clothes, yes. We, had to take them off when we got home, put our ordinary ones on. Well of course when you come to think, mother wouldn't be able to do it with such a lot of - we had to keep our things nice.
\par I:\tab How long would they be your Sunday clothes?
\par AH:\tab Oh quite a long time. Only if we were going anywhere special we would put those on.
\par I:\tab What happened to them as they gradually got worn?
\par AH:\tab Well you could wear them weekdays you see. Then - a new lot for Sundays.
\par I:\tab Were there any Sunday school outings that you remember?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, lovely. Every year we had a Sunday school outing.
\par I:\tab Where did you go?
\par AH:\tab 
We used to go away in a brake with horses. Yes, we used to go - to the farms round about you know. Mesonby way we used to and we used to play in the hay loft and - oh, have a whale of a time. It was lovely. And then of course they - we had races, games an
d - and everything when we went. Yes.
\par I:\tab What other social activities organised by the chapel did you take part in, did you belong to anything else, you say you were in the choir?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you belong to anything else?
\par AH:\tab Yes, I was in the Guild.
\par I:\tab Before 1918?
\par AH:\tab Yes. And -
\par I:\tab What Guild was that?
\par AH:\tab It's - well - they call it - they called it the Wesley Guild and - they have different nights you know - a social night, a devotional evening, a literary evening, and - we used to get all - speakers f
or all those. The Guild was a wonderful place. And every month we had a social.
\par I:\tab How often did you go?
\par AH:\tab Once a week. Every Monday night. And we had a social once a month, for all - young people. And - well you see we didn't have much else to go on.
\par I:\tab There was no television to watch was there?
\par AH:\tab No. Oh no.
\par I:\tab Anything else you belonged to?
\par AH:\tab Well not - not before - I was only - what fifteen, then wasn't I - 1918. Oh no. I'd be nineteen. I'd be nineteen. Oh yes, I was then. I was - yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You belonged to the Wesley Guild when you were still at school?
\par AH:\tab Yes, and I was - I went into choir when I was fourteen. Yes.
\par I:\tab What were the activities of the choir?
\par AH:\tab I think the choir has played more part in my life than anything else. We had Mr Ben 
Bishop as conductor and he taught us all - you know, we sang a - an anthem every Sunday morning and nights. And he taught us all - all the lovely music I know came from him. I sang in 'The Messiah' every year. Yes. I was in the very first - very first tim
e
 'The Messiah' was given, I was in it. And it's - it was given every year after that. And not only that, we had - we used to sing in the spring we used to give Creation or the - all the oratorios we used to go in for. And - I have - and then of course we 
had a choir concert every year, and we used to do 'Lohengrin' and all those lovely things. And we always used to have an orchestra too.
\par I:\tab So music has played a big part in your life?
\par AH:\tab Music - oh yes, played a very big part in my life. Yes, yes.
\par I:\tab Did the church have an outing at all - a choir outing?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, there was always a chair outing, yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Where did you go can the choir outing?
\par AH:\tab Well - we used to go to Scarborough or Saltburn, places like that. And often into the country. We used to love the country ones. Middleton-in-Teesdale, places like that. Beautiful.
\par I:\tab How many were in the choir?
\par AH:\tab Well it was a choir - it was always full. It was a big choir.
\par I:\tab Did the chapel run any temperance club?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you belong to any other club organised by the church?
\par AH:\tab Well I think that'll come in my next one. About the temperance.
\par I:\tab Did the chapel run a temperance club?
\par AH:\tab No, not - oh we used to have - of course we did - we had a Band of Hope when I was a child, yes.
\par I:\tab Were you a member or not?
\par AH:\tab Yes, I was and I signed the pledge. Yes.
\par I:\tab What did the Band of Hope do then?
\par AH:\tab Oh it was wonderful, it was every Wednesday night an
d we used to get our schoolroom packed with children and we used to sing all the old gospel things and they used to show us slides on a lantern about - men being drunk and coming home and - it was wonderful, we had the most wonderful time. Oh it was marve
llous, the Band of Hope. I don't think there would be so many young folks drink if they had something like that nowadays.
\par I:\tab Did they have any other activities for the Band of Hope, did you do anything else with them?
\par AH:\tab Not at the church, no. But we were 
all got to sign the pledge. Yes. You know, and we used to go so long and then they to ask you if you would like to sign the card. Say you wouldn't - abstain from all intoxicating liquor. I've kept that up all my life. Yes. Yes. Yes. I don't think I'm a sp
oilsport. No.
\par I:\tab Was grace said at meals in your family?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Every Sunday, just Sunday when we were all together.
\par I:\tab Who said it?
\par AH:\tab Well my eldest brother used to say it and then I started to say it. That was every Sunday when we were all together.
\par I:\tab Were you taught to say prayers at night?
\par AH:\tab We always said our prayers when we went to bed.
\par I:\tab Did you ever have family prayers?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab You just said your own prayers did you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father take an interest in politics?
\par AH:\tab Well he was a very good Liberal. Yes.
\par I:\tab Why do you think he held those views, any idea at all, did he ever say?
\par AH:\tab Well you see, it was when I was younger that he was - I know he was very keen on it all, he never did any - I don' t - I think he some kind
 of canvassing for votes. I think that would be in the time when we had the income. Yes, well that was - that was one of the times Lincoln got in the know he was our M.P. for Darlington.
\par I:\tab What made your father a liberal, did you ever get any idea why he supported the Liberal party?
\par AH:\tab Well I don't know. I think they - the Liberals were more - you - you used to be considered if you were a Conservative in those days you had lots and lots of money and the Liberals were sort of the social - now what can I sa
y - anyhow, father believed in their - beliefs more than anybody, he was a real Liberal. Wore his blue ribbon.
\par I:\tab He felt the Conservatives were for the rich people then?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And the Liberals were more for?
\par AH:\tab The middle class, yes.
\par I:\tab When your father was a blacksmith was it his own business or did he work for somebody?
\par AH:\tab Oh no, he worked for the Darlington Forge. Yes. He first worked in - at - the Felling and of course he was moved from there, they were closed down, and he moved to Darlington - Darlington Forge, and he worked there all his life practically.
\par I:\tab This was a new job he got?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Or did the firm move?
\par AH:\tab Oh the firm moved. Yes. Darlington Forge. And - he was foreman blacksmith. But - he said when you first started you had to 
learn the trade right from the beginning. He shoed horses and that first. Yes, yes. Of course they - they sent him a horse that had - a bad leg, a greasy leg or something, and father refused, to do it. And of course - after that, well he went into the wor
k
s. And - I have a piece somewhere where me father and mother had their golden wedding and - it said about him, he did, the frames for the Beringaria and all - a few of these big ships, the foams and the rudders and in those days - there was no hydraulic t
hings and that. Father had to put all those rivets in with a big hammer. Hammer them all in. He used to come home and his shirts were ringing wet after he'd done it.
\par I:\tab Was he a big man?
\par AH:\tab Yes, he was a - yes. A broad man, not - not as tall but he was very broad. He was very strong.
\par I:\tab Did your mother take an interest in politics?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Not at all?
\par AH:\tab No, she thought that was the man's job. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember your father voting in a general election before 1919?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab In some places at that time men felt they risked losing their job or their house if they voted differently from their employers, do you know if your father felt himself under that kind of pressure to vote, for a particular party?
\par AH:\tab No, only Uncle Robert didn't believe in who he voted for because he was a bit Conservative. And Uncle Robert was managing director of the - Darlington Forge. Father - stuck to his - no, no.
\par I:\tab Was he actually a member of the Liberal party or not?
\par AH:\tab I can't say. I should think he would be.
\par I:\tab But you do remember him working for the Liberal party?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your mother help when your father was working at an election?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab Did your father take part in any political activity other than at election time?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab When your parents were not doing their work how did they spend their time?
\par AH:\tab My father played cricket on the Saturday afternoon.
\par I:\tab Where did he play cricket?
\par AH:\tab For Cockertan.
\par I:\tab Did you go and watch him?
\par AH:\tab Yes. I did. And mother did. And of course some Saturdays they went away to play.
\par I:\tab Did he do anything else?
\par AH:\tab No. All the boys - all my brothers were footballers and cricketers.
\par I:\tab And your father played the concertina and that?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And made puppets?
\par AH:\tab That was the only one he made, yes.
\par I:\tab I suppose our mother didn't have much spare time did she?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab What were her hobbies, how did she spend her time?
\par AH:\tab Well sewing and baking. Sewing and that. But - there was one thing - everything had to be finished before five o'clock, whatever we 
were doing, for the - for the family coming in. Mother never worked after - at night-time. No. Always had to be done.
\par I:\tab So when you'd finished your evening meal you could all be together?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. We - 'cos us girls when we got older we sat knitting and - mother taught us all to do all crewing and knitting.
\par I:\tab So she didn't have any other hobbies then?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did your mother have any interests outside the home at all?
\par AH:\tab 
Well - she did at church. She was in the ladies sewing party, they worked hard, they - we used to have sales of work every - yes, meet once a week - once a week, Wednesday afternoon they all went to the sewing meeting. And - she used to enjoy it, she used
 to come home - go about three o'clock and come home about nine. Eeh they used to make - tremendous amount of money for the church. And she used to go to the Minister's class an a Thursday afternoon. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of a class was that?
\par AH:\tab You know, Bible - a sort of Bible class, yes.
\par I:\tab Did she ever go out to enjoy herself?
\par AH:\tab Well she'd go to see a friend that was all you know.
\par I:\tab Did your mother and father ever go out together?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, yes. He used to take her out on a Friday night, leave me to - 
on not when we were younger though. Well of course grandma would look after them, yes, he used to take her to the Hippodrome and the theatre. There was a Theatre Royale in those days. Yes, once a week.
\par I:\tab Did she ever go out with anyone else apart from your father?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab Did she have any particular friend?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab What time did your father get home from work in the evenings?
\par AH:\tab Well - it was all hours. Sometimes he worked all day and all night. I think had a rush job, yes. He was never home at five o'clock ever. He was always - they always worked later.
\par I:\tab About what time would it be then?
\par AH:\tab Sometimes six or seven and then of course if he went on working - yes.
\par I:\tab How many evenings a week would he spend at home?
\par AH:\tab Well he never went out much. No.
\par I:\tab Did your father attend any clubs?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Or pubs?
\par AH:\tab He used to often have a drink, yes.
\par I:\tab Did he go regularly for a drink?
\par AH:\tab Not every night. But he enjoyed a drink.
\par I:\tab How often would he go?
\par AH:\tab Well I should think bout three times a week.
\par I:\tab Did he go to one that was near?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your mother ever go with him?
\par AH:\tab Never.
\par I:\tab Did your father take part in any sport, you say he played cricket?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did he ever attend the races?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did he bet at all?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did your father belong to any savings clubs?
\par AH:\tab Not that I know of.
\par I:\tab Boot club, sick club, funeral club or anything like that?
\par AH:\tab No. Mother had - me mother had one for the doctor. Yes. Yes. Just the doctor yes. I think she used to pay a shilling a week.
\par I:\tab How did that work?
\par AH:\tab Well if anyone was ill he came you see. That was instead of sending bills in, they paid a shilling week when they wanted -
\par I:\tab They paid that direct to the doctor did they?
\par AH:\tab Yes, Yes.
\par I:\tab So that was a sort of sick club that your mother paid?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab But your father didn't?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab How did you get on with your brothers and sisters?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, very well.
\par I:\tab Was there any one you felt particularly close to?
\par AH:\tab My brother Tom, he and I were good friends.
\par I:\tab As a child who did you play with?
\par AH:\tab Well it was the children at school.
\par I:\tab Did you play with any neighbours at all?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And the children at school?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Where did you usually play?
\par AH:\tab Well we sometimes went - came into our house. Mother - if it was a wet day. Or we went into the park. And I was a good player of diabolo in those days. Yes. I could toss it as high as the treetops. And catch it. I loved it. Loved it.
\par I:\tab Did you ever play in the yard or garden?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you play in the street?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go into other homes to play?
\par AH:\tab Not often.
\par I:\tab Otherwise it was in the park?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab What other games do you remember playing?
\par AH:\tab Oh I - outside? Only when we were young we had hoops, you know. Bowlers as we used to call them. We - we used to get - bowlers. Well, hoops really, yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab We had a stick to hit them with. And - tops and whips when you were children.
\par AH:\tab And chucks. And the boys used to get an iron - hoop you know. Yes, they always got an iron one, the girls had wooden ones. And skipping ropes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What games did you play inside?
\par AH:\tab Well at that - that would be - when I was fourteen. Inside? Such as Ludo and all things when we were children.
\par I:\tab When you were playing outside were you allowed to get dirty?
\par AH:\tab Well mother never said anything.
\par I:\tab It didn't matter?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your parents discourage you from playing with certain children?
\par AH:\tab Not that I know of.
\par I:\tab Can you tell me how old your mother was when she died?
\par AH:\tab Sixty-nine. And she - she died on the third of April 1937.
\par I:\tab Did you find your father's date of birth?
\par AH:\tab He was born on the second of October 1863. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you remember your mother voting an election before 1919?
\par AH:\tab Oh always. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you know which party she would vote for?
\par AH:\tab Liberal.
\par I:\tab Could you describe the game of chucks?
\par AH:\tab Now wait a minute, we had - they were things you just threw up and counted as they dropped. Just can't - they were square in pot. I just can't remember it all. You just threw them up and I think counted as they dropped to the ground. No.
\par I:\tab Did you belong to any youth organisations at all?
\par AH:\tab The Guild at the church. Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you belong to any other organisation?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you have any hobbies while you were still at school, did you keep any pets or collect anything or do any gardening?
\par AH:\tab No, I used to play diabolo. Yes. You've, got that, yes.
\par I:\tab Any hobbies, knitting, sewing, keeping pets or anything?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes. Knitting and sewing. No, all we had was a canary.
\par I:\tab Was it yours?
\par AH:\tab No. Mother's.
\par I:\tab Did you collect anything like stamps or anything like that?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you aver do any gardening?
\par AH:\tab No, not in those days, we didn't have a garden.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go fishing?
\par AH:\tab No. Just for tiddlers when we were young.
\par I:\tab With a jam jar?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you go for walks?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go bicycling?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab When you went far walks who did you go with while you were a schoolgirl?
\par AH:\tab Oh well we had school friends. But very often I had to take my sister - one - the youngest out.
\par I:\tab Did you take part in any sport?
\par AH:\tab Now, is this after - well we just - we just did the games at school. Drilling and - drilling in the playground and then of course we played with the skipping ropes and that.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go to any theatres or concerts or music halls, while you were at school?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab What did you go to?
\par AH:\tab Well there was the Darlington Theatre. Of course we went to father - father or mother, we never went alone.
\par I:\tab What sort of things did you see there?
\par AH:\tab Well - we got all kinds that came to Darlington in those days, there were operas and musical comedies and - Darlington was quite a good place in those days. The Theatre Royal was at the bottom of Corporation Road. Yes.
\par I:\tab It wasn't where the Civic Theatre is now?
\par AH:\tab No, it was at the bottom of Corporation Road. But there was the Hippodrome. We used to get nearly all the operas t
o the Hippodrome and we used to queue up and go in the gods we used to call the. And - oh, we got some lovely things to come to Darlington. I can't understand why we don't have them now.
\par I:\tab They can't get the support now can they?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Where was the Hippodrome?
\par AH:\tab Still where the Civic Theatre is. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you ever go to any music halls?
\par AH:\tab Well the only music hall we had was the Central Hall, you know, which is the old rate offices, you know in Bull Wynd and - I know they used
 to get some lovely singers and my brother and I used to go on a Wednesday night. It was a shilling to get in but they had lovely tenors and - contraltos and that. We always used to enjoy it. I've always been very fond of music.
\par I:\tab Did you go to any cinemas while you were still at school?
\par AH:\tab Yes. There was the - Arcade Cinema in those days. That's where the bingo hall is now in Skinnergate. No, in Skinnergate - the bingo hall.
\par I:\tab It used to be the Majestic Ballroom didn't it?
\par AH:\tab Yes, it did. Yes. Yes, we used to go to matinees of course on a afternoon, Saturday afternoon, we used to go. And I think it used to be about three pence to get in.
\par I:\tab Who took you there?
\par AH:\tab And of course it was all the old pictures - Charlie Chaplin and Mary Pickford and all those - I can - we're seeing them all now on television. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Who did you go with to the cinema?
\par AH:\tab Well - generally with my sisters, we all used to go.
\par I:\tab Did your parents give you any pocket money when you were a schoolgirl?
\par AH:\tab Yes, penny a week. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you get that regularly?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Every Saturday.
\par I:\tab What did you spend the penny on?
\par AH:\tab Well you could get quite a lot for a penny in those days. You get a whole quarter of packets chocolate for a penny. And you can get - you could get ha'penny
 bars of Fry's chocolate. And they were - about that size - a good size for a ha'penny. And of course you had Spanish and Kali suckers and all.
\par I:\tab So it would be sweets you spent it on?
\par AH:\tab Yes, it was.
\par I:\tab Did anyone outside the home help your mother look after her house and family? Any relations, friends or neighbours?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab If your mother was ill or confined to bed how did she manage?
\par AH:\tab Well it was father and the eldest of us to - to look after mother.
\par I:\tab Do you remember what happened when one of your younger brothers or sisters was born?
\par AH:\tab Oh well we never knew, they were all born at home but we never knew anything about it. No. Not until we knew we had a baby brother or a sister.
\par I:\tab Who looked after your mother then?
\par AH:\tab Well - there was a person - a friend of hers used to come in and - look after her during the day but father did the night work and that. Yes. Used to make her gruel.
\par I:\tab What was in that?
\par AH:\tab Well mother used to love it, he used to put sultanas into it, it's a bit like porridge. But I think it's thinner than that and - he used to make her that every night.
\par I:\tab Was this friend who came in a neighbour?
\par AH:\tab Well she lived - up Harrowgate Hill. And of course we had grandma you know, grandma helped. Yes. But you know, they didn't go to hospital to have their babies in those days.
\par I:\tab So you'd have a surprise when there was a new baby in the family did you?
\par AH:\tab Yes we did. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your parents have any relatives living nearby?
\par AH:\tab Just my Uncle Robert - living - yes.
\par I:\tab How much did they see of them?
\par AH:\tab Well just - just - if they were - mother used to go up sometime on an afternoon to see Auntie Annie, but - they always met at Christmas time.
\par I:\tab Where did they meet?
\par AH:\tab Well mother went to their house and they came to ours afterwards you know. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your parents have many friends?
\par AH:\tab Oh - well of course, mother had more church friends. You know, she went to chapel and - and the minister's class and she had her friends at church.
\par I:\tab Did they share the same friends?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Where did your mother see her friends, was it at church?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did she see her friends anywhere else?
\par AH:\tab Well just this friend that lived up Harrowgate Hill, she used to come to tea and mother used to go to her house for tea.
\par I:\tab How had she got to know her do you know?
\par AH:\tab She said she just got to know her when she first came to Darlington from the Felling and - they became firm friends. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father have friends of his own?
\par AH:\tab No, I don't think so.
\par I:\tab Did he share any of your mother's friends at all?
\par AH:\tab Well of course he was always pleased when they came to tea or anything like that.
\par I:\tab They were your mother's friends?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes, they were.
\par I:\tab Were friends ever invited into the home?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes.
\par I:\tab About how often did you have friends in the home?
\par AH:\tab Well this person came often. And then of course if we had a birthday - mother always gave us a special tea and we could have a friend in to tea. And of course Christmas it was the same, we could have friends in at Christmas.
\par I:\tab Would they be offered anything to eat or drink - you said they came to tea?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Would they normally be offered something to eat or drink?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, always.
\par I:\tab Would they just drop in or did they come on special occasions?
\par AH:\tab Oh they dropped in as well.
\par I:\tab Would you say that the friends invited in then were your mother's friends or your father's friends or both of them?
\par AH:\tab Both of them. Father made everyone very welcome,
\par I:\tab Did friends call in casually without an invitation?
\par AH:\tab Oh I think they would, yes. Yes, especially the chapel people.
\par I:\tab Have you any idea when that would be?
\par AH:\tab I don't think so.
\par I:\tab Would neighbours call in casually without an invitation?
\par AH:\tab We never - they never came into each other's houses unles
s it was for something special, if they were - wanting to borrow something or anything, but - I'm afraid mother didn't believe in - gossiping. But - they were always very welcome if they came. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your parents ever go out to visit friends or neighbours, you said your mother did?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did your father go with your mother at all?
\par AH:\tab Not always, no, not always.
\par I:\tab Did your parents ever visit neighbours?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements, what do you think your parents did when they got together with their friends?
\par AH:\tab Oh well they - they - played a game or cards or dominoes. But never gambled.
\par I:\tab Did they ever make music when they had friends in?
\par AH:\tab Now where are we talking - are we talking after 1918 now. Oh. Oh yes. Yes. Yes. Well I don't think we had our piano then. Yes.
\par I:\tab Many people divide society into different social classes or groups, in that time before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one class and some to another?
\par AH:\tab No, I don't think so. I know there were a lot of poor people in the town. You know, round about John Street and that there were little children running around with no - stockings and shoes, on when I was a girl,
\par I:\tab That was the poor area?
\par AH:\tab Yes, it was.
\par I:\tab Where's John Street?
\par AH:\tab You know where Foster Moorlands is in Northgate? Well just - a little bit higher up, they've made a new road of it, John Street. Yes, new by-pass. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab That still is one of the poor areas isn't it?
\par AH:\tab I think so, yes, but not like it used to be. We used to have a ragged school you know. Yes.
\par I:\tab Can you tell me about that?
\par AH:\tab Just that they used to look after the poor children?
\par I:\tab Where was this school?
\par AH:\tab Down Parkgate somewhere. And then there was the - oh dear, Auntie Katie worked - it's now the Salvation Army place. Up - in Park - in Parkgate, yes. Well that was a place for poor people, you know, tramps and everybody to go to and be cared for.

\par I:\tab Were there a lot of poor people in Darlington?
\par AH:\tab There were quite then. And then of course we had the - what was called the workhouse. Not the workhouse now you know, it's East Haven. That was a proper workhouse, yes.
\par I:\tab Did you know any of these families that were very poor?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab You never came into contact with them?
\par AH:\tab No. Just we had one or two girls came to school that were very poor.
\par I:\tab Which class would you say you belonged to?
\par AH:\tab Well now I don't know, me father - we always were kept - very nice. Now there's first, second, third, I suppose - suppose we'd be the second class. Yes, I think so.
\par I:\tab What sort of people belonged to the same class as yourself? What sort of occupations would you say?
\par AH:\tab 
Well where we lived there were various - there was two nice old ladies, they were dressmakers, lived two doors from us, the Miss Stanleys' and they were very - gentle people you know. And - Mrs Redfern at the Post Office, they were very nice. We lived alo
ng quite a lot of nice people. Yes. It was a really nice road.
\par I:\tab What sort of people belonged to the other classes, what sort of occupations would the poorer class have?
\par AH:\tab Well I mean their parents were in a higher position than my father was you see, and of course they have better houses and - those, the better class people.
\par I:\tab What sort of occupations would they be?
\par AH:\tab Well such - do you mean such as my Uncle Robert. Well he was a Managing Director. Of the Darlington Forge. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of occupations would the people of the poor area have?
\par AH:\tab Well I should think most of them would work in the mill. All the girls went to work with shawls and - in those days you know. Oh yes. Used to be known as the mill girls.
\par I:\tab Which mill would that be?
\par AH:\tab Pease's mill.
\par I:\tab Is that a cotton mill?
\par AH:\tab Woollen. Yes.
\par I:\tab And they used to go in, shawls?
\par AH:\tab Yes. They did.
\par I:\tab Do you remember them going?
\par AH:\tab I - yes, I can remember seeing girls in the shawls, oh yes.
\par I:\tab So they were the poorer classes?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Were you ever told to curtsey or show respect in some way to anyone?
\par AH:\tab Not to curtsey but we were always told to - be kind and - how can I put it - to always had to know our manners, we were taught manners.
\par I:\tab That was at home?
\par AH:\tab Yes, at home, and to tell the truth. Those were two of the most important things.
\par I:\tab Did you ever have to show respect in any way to certain people at all?
\par AH:\tab Well we had to father and mother. And to older people. Yes. Yes. That's what's lacking today isn't it. No respect for anybody.
\par I:\tab Was there anyone you called sir or master or madam?
\par AH:\tab No. We called our headmistress miss.
\par I:\tab Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these ways, did anyone ever call them sir or madam?
\par AH:\tab No, it was always Mr and Mrs B.
\par I:\tab In this district who were considered the most important people?
\par AH:\tab Well we had -
\par I:\tab Your Uncle Robert was an important person?
\par AH:\tab Yes, and of co
urse there was Lord and Lady Putman. Yes. And then there was -Sir Charles Starmer. That'd be the first - you know - he married twice. And - oh, there were - we had quite a lot of wealthy people. You see, Darlington's a Quaker town and there where a lot of
 Quakers, their meeting house was in Skinnergate.
\par I:\tab It's still they isn't it?
\par AH:\tab Yes. And they were all - they all - they were all wealthy but my word they gave most of - they gave - they gave an awful lot of money away to poor people. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Why do you think these people were considered important, your Uncle Robert and Lord and Lady Putman?
\par AH:\tab Oh and there was the Pease's, they were part of Darlington, you know. I can't just think of all the names but there were quite a lot of notable people.
\par I:\tab Why were they considered important?
\par AH:\tab Well they did a lot of good work for the town. And - I've belonged lately to the Darlington Women Temperance Association. Well you see the gentlemen as we called them at Darlington formed that because when I was a youn
g girl you were always seeing drunken men going around the streets. You see they could get liquor from early morning. Public houses were open all day long. And sometimes men never went to work - went to the pubs instead. And these people formed a place wh
ere they could go and have a hot cup of tea, they used to go out and - let these people go in for hot cups of tea and that. They did wonderful work.
\par I:\tab Where would they do this, where would it be?
\par AH:\tab Well I should think it would Friends Meeting House, yes.
\par I:\tab They did a lot of good work there didn't they?
\par AH:\tab They did. The Fothergills, they were well known people as well.
\par I:\tab Why do you think all these people were considered important, you said it's because of the good work they did?
\par AH:\tab I really think that - their lives - they led such good lives that they did all the good they could.
\par I:\tab And that made them important?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Who did the shopkeepers associate with, who did they have for friends?
\par AH:\tab As friends? Oh I don't know. No.
\par I:\tab Who did the clergy associate with?
\par AH:\tab Not really, only they looked after their - flocks as it were didn't they.
\par I:\tab Did they make friends with the people?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes, they visited you and - oh yes.
\par I:\tab Who would you say the teachers associated with?
\par AH:\tab I don't know. We had a wonderful lot of teachers at our school.
\par I:\tab Who did they have for friends, did you ever notice?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab The farmers, who would you say they associated with?
\par AH:\tab Eeh I wouldn't know. No.
\par I:\tab Who do you think the employers associated with, your Uncle Robert was an employer wasn't he?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Well he was also a councillor he was -
\par I:\tab Who did he have for friends?
\par AH:\tab Oh he had an awful lot of friends, but I don't know who they were.
\par I:\tab What sort of people would you say went to church?
\par AH:\tab 
Well - now what - what can I say about that. It was the thing to go to church in those days every Sunday, the whole - there were family pews in our church. Yes. Where the whole family used to sit, they used to have a ticket and a pew and I think they p
aid so much a year for the ticket and the whole family went on a Sunday to church.
\par I:\tab What sort of families would they be?
\par AH:\tab Well of course there were both kinds, rich and poor. Yes.
\par I:\tab What sort of people went to chapel? Was there any difference?
\par AH:\tab No, I don't think so, no,
\par I:\tab Where you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or would you say there were different groups even within the working class?
\par AH:\tab Yes I would. Because - some men made more money than others.
\par I:\tab Could you describe a family within each group of the working class?
\par AH:\tab Well the people that lived - lived next door to us, there were eight children and, their father was in the Army. And - they were - they weren't as well off as we were. My father ha
d a better wage. When their father was away, during the First World War, my father gave every one of those children pocket money every week until their father came back out of the Army. Yes. We looked after them, mother used to give them all and all kinds
 of things.
\par I:\tab Because they were so poor?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Now those people never went to church. But - but when both my father and mother died they both - came to the service in the church,
\par I:\tab They were so appreciative were they?
\par AH:\tab Yes, of my mother and father, yes.
\par I:\tab Do you think that one group within the working class felt itself superior to the rest at all?
\par AH:\tab Well I don't know - we didn't. No.
\par I:\tab Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par AH:\tab Yes, I think so,
\par I:\tab What sort of family was a rough family?
\par AH:\tab Well I mean it was the way they were brought up you know really, some weren't - some were brought up better than others.
\par I:\tab Would that have any connection with the jobs their fathers did or not?
\par AH:\tab Oh I don't think so.
\par I:\tab It was just a difference in the way they were brought up?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember a distinction of this kind between craftsmen and labourers?
\par AH:\tab Oh I don't know. You were thought a bit better if you had a craft because - they had to serve t
heir time hadn't they and - while they were serving their time in those days our mother's never got anything you know, they'd serve their time for nothing.
\par I:\tab So you felt there was a bit of a difference?
\par AH:\tab Perhaps - a little.
\par I:\tab Did your mother and father have the same attitude to people in different classes?
\par AH:\tab They were always kind to everybody. We were taught to be that way. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you think your mother saw herself as belonging to a particular social class?
\par AH:\tab I don't think so. Mother was - I mea
n - they were born in humble homes. But - they were brought up very nicely, they had nice parents and - that were taught - the better, way of life. Some children were allowed to run just wild and we were never allowed to do that.
\par I:\tab But your mother never thought of herself as belonging to a particular class?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab Was it possible at that time to move from one class to another and can you remember anyone who did?
\par AH:\tab Well I suppose it's what we did. We started in a - a very small house and we ended up in a - a very lovely house, we ended up in Greenbank Road which was a lovely house.
\par I:\tab So you moved up?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Was that connected with your father's job at all?
\par AH:\tab Mm.
\par I:\tab Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par AH:\tab 
Oh well there's lots of people I could think of as we thought of real ladies. Because they were so good and - to everybody and - you always thought them as - oh well, she's a lovely - kind person, you know, when we were children, you find things out li
ke that don't you.
\par I:\tab Any other reason why you thought they were real ladies or real gentlemen?
\par AH:\tab I don't know.
\par I:\tab Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par AH:\tab We certainly did.
\par I:\tab What did you think of him?
\par AH:\tab They used to 
try the door handles at night to see that you'd locked the door. I can remember - my sister-in-law saying to her mother - twelve o'clock at night there was a knock on her front door and she stood at the top of the stairs and she shouted who's that? And th
e policemen opened the door and shone his lamp on her, and he said, do - do you know you're front door's open? Oh, she said, is it, just clash it as you go out.
\par I:\tab What did he say to that?
\par AH:\tab Well that's just typical, well you see, they did try doors. A po
liceman were always round in those days. I think that's the trouble today. No, because - the policeman always wore white gloves. And - they used to give children a clip over - over the ear with their gloves if they where doing anything they shouldn't. Yes
.
\par I:\tab What did you think of the police?
\par AH:\tab Oh well we - we would have been terrified. Yes. I don't think they were thought in those days like that are today.
\par I:\tab When you ware naughty did your mother ever say, I'll call a policeman?
\par AH:\tab On no.
\par I:\tab But they just frightened you did they?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How do you think the policeman treated the people?
\par AH:\tab Well I don't - I don't really know, I didn't come in contact much with them. But I know it was an awful thing if anyone had a policeman go to their door in young days. You thought - terrible.
\par I:\tab Was your home rented?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you see anything of your landlord at all?
\par AH:\tab Yes, she used to call.
\par I:\tab What did you feel about her?
\par AH:\tab She was very nice. Very nice. Yes.
\par I:\tab Do you remember feeling that your parents had to struggle to make ends meet at all?
\par AH:\tab Well mother didn't have any easy time when I - we were all young because we were all to bring up and - and she fed us well. She used to think it more important to feed the family than to buy a house. Some peop
le would rather buy a house and go short but never mother thought that way nor father.
\par I:\tab What did you think about the fact that they might have had a bit of a struggle to make ends meet, do you remember whether you thought anything as a child?
\par AH:\tab 
I - I - well when we were - we used to have to - clothes used to get passed on you know. But mother always kept us very nice. I think she must have been a wonderful person. 'Cos - because the lovely meals she made us and that and - and I mean - she could 
make them from very little. Yes.
\par I:\tab What difference did it make to the family when your father was ill or out of work, was he ever ill or out of work?
\par AH:\tab Oh he sometimes was ill but never out of work.
\par I:\tab Did it make much difference when he was ill?
\par AH:\tab Well I think he still got has wages, he did, yes.
\par I:\tab How often would you say he was ill?
\par AH:\tab Oh - not often at all. No. He was a big strong healthy man.
\par I:\tab Did you ever get help from the guardians or the parish?
\par AH:\tab No. They would rather have died. Yes.
\par I:\tab When there was someone in the district whom the people disapproved of very strongly was there any special way in which they showed it - do you remember anyone being made to leave by rough music?
\par AH:\tab No. No. Oh no. No, never.
\par I:\tab Were you given lessons by one of your parents, a tutor or a governess?
\par AH:\tab No. Doctor said I should have had. I'm afraid my parents - wouldn't be able to do that for me.
\par I:\tab Did he think you shouldn't have gone to school?
\par AH:\tab Well I was - off school quite a lot, I used to have bronchitis every winter and - I used to have to stay off school. In fact I left at - when I was just about twelve year old.
\par I:\tab That was through ill health was it?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How old would you be when you first went to school?
\par AH:\tab Five.
\par I:\tab When you first started what time of the morning did you go?
\par AH:\tab Nine o'clock.
\par I:\tab What time did you come back?
\par AH:\tab Four. They always gave the little ones a tea party when they started school. Yes. We used to have little fancy cups and saucers and - yes, first - day you went to school, the new ones all - there was a little tea party. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have things to eat as well?
\par AH:\tab Infants. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you come home for lunch?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How long would you have for lunch?
\par AH:\tab I think it was twelve 'til half past one.
\par I:\tab What kind of a school was it?
\par AH:\tab It was Corporation Road, it's still there. It was a splendid school
\par I:\tab That isn't a church school is it?
\par AH:\tab No, ordinary. Yes. It turned some marvellous scholars out did Corporation Road school.
\par I:\tab Was it a mixed school?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab How did you get to school?
\par AH:\tab Walked.
\par I:\tab How long did it take you?
\par AH:\tab Well it didn't take us long - we lived in Salisbury Terrace, we - just round there, be about five minutes I should think.
\par I:\tab Who went with you to school?
\par AH:\tab Well - just went together. Sisters and - yes.
\par I:\tab And you came home for your midday meal?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab What did you think of school, did you like it or dislike it?
\par AH:\tab I liked it. Yes.
\par I:\tab How did you feel about the teachers?
\par AH:\tab Very nice. But very strict. My word, y
es. And you got the cane in those days if you didn't do what we were told. Or if you were late for school you got the cane. But - nowadays teachers daren't touch them or do anything to them. Well I know my mother, if we went home and told my mother we'd h
ad the cane mother used to say, well you must have done something to deserve it.
\par I:\tab Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life, such as manners or tidiness or punctuality or ways of speaking. You said punctuality?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. Well we h
ad a wonderful headmistress, she used to teach us how to - the correct way to walk. Standing on our toes, yes, and shoulders back. Yes, she taught - she used to come behind you and - get those shoulders back and -she was a wonderful - headmistress but ver
y strict.
\par I:\tab How about manners when you were at school?
\par AH:\tab My word, you daren't answer back or anything like that.
\par I:\tab What about tidiness?
\par AH:\tab Well we always had to - have our hair tied back with ribbons to keep it off the desk you know. Had plaits.
\par I:\tab What about ways of speaking?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes, they did, you had to speak properly.
\par I:\tab If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen, you said you got the cane sometimes?
\par AH:\tab And of course there was the black book for those that - well it was a black book where your name was put down and I suppose - they used to say that if you got it in so many times you got expelled.
\par I:\tab Did anyone ever get expelled?
\par AH:\tab Not to my knowledge. No.
\par I:\tab Did you get the cane as well as going in the black book?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Were the children punished in any other way?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did the girls get the same punishment as the boys?
\par AH:\tab Oh I don't know about the boys. We were at this side of the railings and the boys at the other side of the railings, yes.
\par I:\tab You said you could get the cane for being late, for what other offences do you ever remember anyone getting the cane?
\par AH:\tab Well I should I think it would be cheeking the teacher and - doing - something they shouldn't do.
\par I:\tab Did your parents show an interest in - your schoolwork -at all?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they ask you what you did at school?
\par AH:\tab Mm-hm.
\par I:\tab Did they ever visit the school?
\par AH:\tab No. No, they didn't have open days. No.
\par I:\tab Did they ever meet the teachers at all?
\par AH:\tab No. I should think - perhaps before we went to school - our mothers would have to go and have ran interview with the teacher. But I can't remember that.
\par I:\tab Did the other children at the school come from similar types of home to your own or not?
\par AH:\tab Oh they came from all kinds of homes.
\par I:\tab Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par AH:\tab Not that I know of, only - we didn't sit examinations for the High School. I think the best girls were chosen in those days to go to the High School, those that had done the best work. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did they get any extra help with coaching?
\par AH:\tab Not that I know of.
\par I:\tab Were there any gangs or groups in the school?
\par AH:\tab Not that I know of.
\par I:\tab Were there any children who were left out of things?
\par AH:\tab Well I should - I suppose sometimes it must be like that mustn't it. All children don't join in do they.
\par I:\tab Do you remember anyone being left out?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Were there any of these very poor children at your school?
\par AH:\tab Yes, we had some,
\par I:\tab Did they join in everything or were they left out?
\par AH:\tab I don't think they were left out.
\par I:\tab Did you go any other school?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab You were twelve when you left school?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Would you have stayed longer if you had have had the opportunity?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You left because you had bronchitis?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you attend any part time education afterwards?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Any evening classes or anything like that?
\par AH:\tab No. There was plenty to do at home.
\par I:\tab Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par AH:\tab Well I suppose that'll come later, there was only one thing I ever wanted to be from being a small child and that was a nurse. Yes. I wanted badly to be a nurse but - I was needed at home so I had to stop at home.
\par I:\tab You never got a chance to train?
\par AH:\tab No. I've had quite a lot to do as a matter of fact nursing all through me life. If I haven't been a nurse I've had quite a lot of it to do.
\par I:\tab Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par AH:\tab Well I enjoyed school. The only thing I didn't like was the a
rithmetic. Oh no, I did not. But I liked all the other - drawing and painting and - history and all those subjects I liked and singing. We always had singing lesson on a Friday. I enjoyed all those but I did not like arithmetic. I suppose - I suppose it w
a
s because I wasn't very much at school you see. Yes. Yes. Yes. But I've taught myself far more since I've left school through reading good books and - oh yes, yes. And always looking in the dictionary, I do a lot of crossword puzzles. They've done me a lo
t of good.
\par I:\tab Anything you don't know you look up?
\par AH:\tab I go to the dictionary, yes.
\par I:\tab While you were at school did you have any part time jobs or any means or earning a little regular money?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you have a job at all when you left school?
\par AH:\tab When I was young, no. When I left school? Later on. I'll tell you about that later on perhaps. You're not on to -
\par I:\tab You didn't have any part time jobs while you were at school?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab What was your first full time job?
\par AH:\tab Well the first job I ever had I went as nursemaid to a person and mother let me go there, this lady came to ask if I would go and look after her little boy because she thought I would get out into the fresh air and - do him good. And it did.

\par I:\tab What years would this be?
\par AH:\tab I would just be about - I'd be about thirteen I think. Oh no, 19 - you are - thinking about 18 now are you?
\par I:\tab When do you think you would go as a nursemaid?
\par AH:\tab Oh it was before that.
\par I:\tab Straight away after leaving school?
\par AH:\tab Mm. To get out in to the fresh air.
\par I:\tab So you were born in 1899?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab So if you were thirteen that would be 1912?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You went as a nursemaid in 1912?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab That was a full time job was it?
\par AH:\tab Yes. I called myself a nursemaid. I wasn't really you know.
\par I:\tab Did you live in at all?
\par AH:\tab No. The lady had the fruit shop on the corner of - our Terrace. And she just - we used to get all our fruit and vegetables there and she used to - she just asked mother if I could take the little boy out and she thought it would
 do me good, and it did you see. Oh it made a wonderful difference.
\par I:\tab How long did you carry on with this job?
\par AH:\tab For about a year.
\par I:\tab Did you go any other jobs after that?
\par AH:\tab No. Well I had to stay and help mother then.
\par I:\tab Did you do any housework at all far this lady?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab You just took the little boy out?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Have you done any jobs since the First World War?
\par AH:\tab I once went up to help a lady - her husband was ill and I went up there for a few weeks. Yes, just a few weeks.
\par I:\tab Do you remember what year that was?
\par AH:\tab Oh no, I don't.
\par I:\tab Would you have preferred another type of occupation than staying at home?
\par AH:\tab No. Well, yes, I'd liked to have gone as a nurse, yes. But you know in those days the eldest daughter was considered - it was considered right for her to stay at home. Yes, it was.
\par I:\tab Would you say that doing that job changed your general attitude to life in any way at all?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab You continued to live at home after you left school didn't you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab Did starting full time work change your relationship with your parents at all?
\par AH:\tab No, no. No.
\par I:\tab Or with your brothers and sisters?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you spend your Sunday any differently after you left school?
\par AH:\tab Well - we used to go for walks on a Sunday afternoon. Go to the South Park, walk there and walk back and then go to chapel on a Sunday night at six o'clock and come out about half past seven, go to the South Park again and walk all the way back.

\par I:\tab Did you continue to go to Sunday school?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes, I started as a Sunday school teacher. Yes.
\par I:\tab How old would you be then?
\par AH:\tab I think I started - I'd be about twenty-six when I started Sunday school teaching. And I started with little ones and then I went up to fourteen year olds. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you stay right on at Sunday school until you became a Sunday school teacher? Or did you have a break?
\par AH:\tab No. I went to Sunday school and - yes.
\par I:\tab Did you take an interest in politics at all?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab You didn't take an interest in politics?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you have any particular views at all?
\par AH:\tab No, I don't think so. Of course as soon as we got the vote I voted.
\par I:\tab What did you vote?
\par AH:\tab Well I - I suppose I voted the same as father. Liberal.
\par I:\tab Any particular reason why you'd vote Liberal, just because of your father was it?
\par AH:\tab No, we thought that they were the - right people to vote for. Yes. I still do, if they could only get in.
\par I:\tab Could you say why you think they're the right people to vote for?
\par AH:\tab Well I think they have better ideas and that. I think the Conservative - the Liberals - are more for the - what can I say - the social - the middle class people. Where I think the Conservatives are for the richer folks.
\par I:\tab Did you ever feel under any pressure from anyone to vote for a particular party?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Were you a member of a political party or not?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you ever work for one of the parties at an election?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you take part in any political activity other than at election times?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab You told me earlier something of how you spent your spare time, did you continue to spend your spare time in the same way now you'd left school or did you do different things now?
\par AH:\tab Well I think I would be getting up to the First World War aren't we now? Well I think I sold flags every Saturday. Yes, I did. For - for - the war. Yes.
\par I:\tab What did they do with that money, what was it for?
\par AH:\tab Well it all went towards - I don't know really, it was all for soldiers and sailors. And I was on every week. I was all over Darlington but I - I - I loved 
doing it. And we used to sell from about nine o'clock in the morning 'til four in the afternoon.
\par I:\tab Any other ways in which you spent your spare time?
\par AH:\tab And then of course after the war finished it still went - went on flag days for children's homes and - yes, I carried on.
\par I:\tab Did you do anything else in your spare time?
\par AH:\tab Well, we - during the war you mean? Well we used to go to the church mornings, used to knit helmets and things for the soldiers. And we used to - have singing parties and that. Of cou
rse we used to have soldiers come into our homes. Yes. They were invited in on a Sunday night; those that came to church were invited into people's homes for their supper on a Sunday night. Or they could come in any time. Then they were on leave or -

\par I:\tab You'd have left school just before the First World War wouldn't you?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab How did you spend your spare time then? Very differently?
\par AH:\tab I don't - suppose you know, working for bazaars and - first - I started first with the bran tub with - as
 a child you know. Yes, I used to do that and then - then I started on the confectionery stall at the bazaar, you used to make an awful lot of money on there.
\par I:\tab Did you go out in the evening after you left school?
\par AH:\tab Just to chapel. To what was on at the chapel during the week.
\par I:\tab Who would you go to chapel with?
\par AH:\tab Well I had - I'd got a special friend then you see, I had a girlfriend then.
\par I:\tab Did she live near you?
\par AH:\tab Yes, she didn't live far away.
\par I:\tab Did you make any new friends, boys or girls, at this time?
\par AH:\tab Oh well of course we made boyfriends as well as girlfriends.
\par I:\tab How did you meet them?
\par AH:\tab Well, we - after church really. We used to go for walks on Sunday nights and - then of course it was very difficult because the war came and they all we
nt away. A lot - and a lot of them never came back. My brother was one of them, he was killed when he was twenty-one. I can remember - one Sunday - the Seaforth Highlanders came to Darlington, they'd marched, I don't know where from, an awful long way, a 
r
oute march. And they were billeted in Corporation Road Day School and I can remember mother cut all our - the remains of our joint - she cut it up into sandwiches. Everyone was running with sandwiches and jugs of tea down to the school to give these soldi
e
rs. And you know, they were beautiful, they had their tartan kilts and all the buckles. They looked - such fine handsome men and yet we - we were told that not one of them came back. They went straight into battle. They were marvellous - a marvellous set 
o
f men. And then after that of course - ew - I don't know what happened, where - where did we go to school because the schools was taken for the soldiers, I think we just have gone into the Methodist schoolroom. Because - troops were billeted all the time 
y
ou see and used to go on route marches and - I know my mother used to keep tight hold of me, I wasn't allowed to go down to the schools there, all soldiers were. And then of course after that they were all billeted up at Hummers Knott. Yes. They had a cam
p - a big camp. They were all fields. Well you know when I was young there was nothing else but fields in Darlington, all Coniscliffe Road there was no houses. It's changed an awful lot. Yes. Was. Yes
\par I:\tab Did you ever bring your friend's home?
\par AH:\tab Yes. And the boys brought their friend's home. Yes.
\par I:\tab Did you have any special friends at this time, you had a girl friend didn't you?
\par AH:\tab Yes. And then I got a boyfriend. But he was no good. No. I have never - it's a funny thing, I've never ever wanted t
o be married. No, I've been quite content - to be doing things for others. So - it isn't for everybody to get married you know. Is it. Yes. Yes. I never longed for things you know. My life's been quite full up of interesting things. I've never had time - 
I
 had just said to me - perhaps I shouldn't say this - my hairdresser said to me she said, you know Miss B., we've been wondering about you. We get so many in that's crabby and bad tempered and you don't seem to be like that at all. I said, well I've not -
 not any need to be, I said, my life's been full of - full enough. Yes.
\par I:\tab Where would you go with the special boyfriend you had then?
\par AH:\tab For walks. Yes. There was nowhere else to go.
\par I:\tab Where would you go for walks?
\par AH:\tab Well there was some - it was beauti
ful all round Darlington you know, there was - we used to go to the South Park and then right on right round Carmel Road back home. And then of course there was what we called Black Path in those days. Yes. Round by Linden Avenue, there was a lovely walk 
t
hrough there, into Carmel Road, you got straight through there. And then of course what is now Brinkburn Road, that was all fields, we used to go in there after school and pick daisies and buttercups. We had - very - a very little way to go before we were
 in fields. And of course there was always round the Tees to go for a walk. That was a lovely walk, yes. I say children will lose the use of their legs because they do nothing but ride in cars these days.
\par I:\tab Where could you go with your special girlfriends?
\par AH:\tab 
Well just went walks, on Saturday afternoon we used to walk from here to Middleton-on-Row and back. Take our tea, pack our tea and have it in the woods at Middleton-one-Row and then walk back again. Yes. Or Croft. We used to walk to Croft and go throu
gh the woods.
\par I:\tab That's quite a walk isn't it?
\par AH:\tab Yes, it is.
\par I:\tab It's very nice by he river isn't it?
\par AH:\tab Very nice.
\par I:\tab Did your parents meet your fiends?
\par AH:\tab Oh yes.
\par I:\tab Did your parents expect to know where you were when you were out?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes. And we had to be home by nine o'clock. Yes, we had. Unless we were going anywhere very special and then that was different. We got permission. But we must be home if we were just going walking or anything by nine o'clock.
\par I:\tab How long did this go on for?
\par AH:\tab Eeh - I should think up to I was eighteen. Yes.
\par I:\tab When you were looking after this little boy did you just take him for walks or did you look after him any other way?
\par AH:\tab No, I just took him out. I used to undress him and put him to bed at night and sometimes he laid on the bed 'til he went to sleep. At six o'clock he was put to bed, and that's all I did,
\par I:\tab And you still lived at home then?
\par AH:\tab Yes. Yes.
\par I:\tab You've remembered another job you've done since the First World War?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab What was that?
\par AH:\tab 
Well - a gentleman from our church lost his wife and his daughter came round to see me if I would go and look after them, for just a little while because, you see, my father had had this awful accident and - he couldn't go to work any more and - it affect
ed his brain a little I think. A corrugated sheet of iron was blown by the wind down - they were mending the roof at works and it came down and caught father right across there.
\par I:\tab When would this be?
\par AH:\tab Oh - I think he would be just about sixty-five. And 
of course - he was in hospital. And then they sent him home to die, they said they could do nothing else for him. Well, I nursed him with a nurse that used to come in. This head was to dress and everything and nurse just said to me - they brought him home
 
Christmas Eve - and the nurse said well they usually had Christmas Day off - did I think I could manage? So I took over and I - after that I used to dress his head, it used to - it had to be dressed a few times a day and I used to do it in between the nur
s
e coming. And - in the end they went to live with my brother. He took a bigger house in Corporation Road and they went to live with father and mother so that made me, I - I hadn't much to do see. So I took this, I went round to this gentleman and saw him 
a
nd I started and I was only going to stay until they got a housekeeper. But it happened - it lasted for six years. And I got ten shilling a week. And I lived in. But it was a lovely post, there was - he was so kind, and the daughter too. And then - I had 
t
o leave because my brother's wife was ill and he begged of me to go home and - I went home and I was home for thirty-six years with my brother and his wife. Until his wife died you see. Just a year ago the wife - his wife died. He died eight years before.
 And I stayed with that woman until she died and then I've got this flat now. Yes.
\par I:\tab How did you get your first nursemaid job?
\par AH:\tab Well the lady came and asked mother if I would go and take the little boy out. And mother thought it would do me good to get out in the fresh air.
\par I:\tab And you just had to take him out?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab And sometimes put him to bed?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab What hours did you work?
\par AH:\tab Oh I used to go about nine o'clock and finish at six at night.
\par I:\tab Did you go on Sundays and Saturdays?
\par AH:\tab Oh no, not Sunday. Nor Saturday.
\par I:\tab Did you have a half-day off at all?
\par AH:\tab Yes, Wednesday afternoon the shop closed and I got that off.
\par I:\tab Did you have any holidays with pay?
\par AH:\tab No. No.
\par I:\tab You were only there twelve months weren't you?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab What were you paid?
\par AH:\tab Eeh I can't remember, it wouldn't be very much. I can't remember, I know I always got some lovely - a lovely packet of sweets and I know that - I got as much fruit during the week as I wanted. Yes, because it's a funny thing, I seemed - after I 
was fourteen I changed altogether, I - and I - never get bronchitis or anything now, it all left me. And I think it was getting out into all that fresh air.
\par I:\tab You've no idea at all what you were paid?
\par AH:\tab No.
\par I:\tab Did you feel you got a fair wage for what you were doing?
\par AH:\tab Well of course if it was a shilling a week it was a lot in those days wasn't it.
\par I:\tab Did you give any of the money to your mother?
\par AH:\tab Oh it all went to mother.
\par I:\tab Do you know what it was spent on?
\par AH:\tab Well I should think it would be food.
\par I:\tab How did you get on with the people you worked with?
\par AH:\tab Very well.
\par I:\tab Was there anybody else employed there that you met?
\par AH:\tab Just the daily person that went in to do the work. And they had a son as well, an elder son.
\par I:\tab How did you get on with the daily help?
\par AH:\tab Oh very well. She was very nice.
\par I:\tab How did your employer treat you?
\par AH:\tab Very good.
\par I:\tab How did you feel about him or her?
\par AH:\tab Just that they were both very nice indeed. Yes.
\par I:\tab Was the son nice too?
\par AH:\tab Yes.
\par I:\tab How did you feel about the work you were doing, did you like it or dislike it?
\par AH:\tab I liked it very much.
